{"title_page": "Cochrane's Craft", "text_new": "{{Infobox religion\n| name                = Cochrane's Craft\n| image               = \n| imagewidth          = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| abbreviation        = \n| type                = [[Traditional witchcraft]]\n| main_classification = \n| orientation         = \n| scripture           = \n| theology            = Polytheism / Pluriform Monotheism\n| polity              = \n| governance          = \n| structure           = \n| leader_title        = \n| leader_name         =\n| leader_title1       = \n| leader_name1        = \n| leader_title2       = \n| leader_name2        = \n| fellowships_type    =\n| fellowships         = \n| fellowships_type1   =\n| fellowships1        =\n| associations        = \n| area                = \n| headquarters        = \n| founder             = Robert Cochrane (legally Roy Bowers)\n| founded_date        = 1951\n| founded_place       = \n| separated_from      = \n| parent              = \n| merger              = \n| absorbed            =\n| separations         = \n| merged_into         =\n| defunct             =\n| congregations_type  = Coven\n| congregations       =\n| members             = Unknown\n| ministers_type      = \n| ministers           = \n| missionaries        =\n| temples             =\n| hospitals           = \n| nursing_homes       = \n| aid                 = \n| primary_schools     = \n| secondary_schools   = \n| tertiary            = \n| other_names         = Cochranianism\n| publications        = \n| website             = \n| footnotes           = \n}}\n\n'''Cochrane's Craft''', which is also known as '''Cochranianism''', is a form of [[traditional witchcraft]] founded in 1951 by the [[English people|English]] witch [[Robert Cochrane (witch)|Robert Cochrane]], who himself claimed to have been taught in the tradition by some of his elderly family members, a claim that is disputed by some historians such as [[Ronald Hutton]] and [[Leo Ruickbie]].<ref name=\"Roebuck\">{{cite book |last1=Cochrane |first1=Robert|last2=Jones|first2=Evan John|editor1-last=Howard|editor1-first=Mike |date= |title=Roebuck in the Thicket:An Anthology of the Robert Cochrane Witchcraft Tradition|publisher=Capall Bann|}}</ref>\n\nDespite numerous practical and theological similarities to other forms of modern witchcraft, such as Gardnerian Wicca, Cochrane's Craft sets itself apart from other traditions in many notable ways, such as its emphasis on the pursuit of wisdom as the highest goal of witchcraft<ref name=\"Second Letter to Joe Wilson\">{{cite letter |title= Second Letter to Joe Wilson|first=Robert |last=Cochrane |recipient= Joe Wilson|date= 1966-01-05|url= http://1734-witchcraft.org/lettertwo.htmlf |accessdate= 2019-06-27}}</ref> and Cochrane's insistence that witchcraft is not [[Paganism|Pagan]] and, in fact, has no more in common with Paganism than does Qabbalah.<ref name=\"Letters to Bill Grey\">{{cite letter |title= Letters to Bill Grey|first=Robert |last=Cochrane |recipient= Bill Grey|url= http://clanoftubalcain.org.uk/the_letters/letters_Bill_Gray_lk.pdf |accessdate= 2019-06-27}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nAround the time that the British [[1735 Witchcraft Act]] was repealed in 1951, and it became legal to practice [[witchcraft]] in the [[United Kingdom]], Cochrane, who was in his early twenties, founded a [[coven]], and named it the [[Clan of Tubal Cain]] after the biblical figure [[Tubal-cain]] (the first blacksmith), as a reference to his work in that profession.\n\nCochrane [[Initiation|initiated]] his wife Jane and several others into the craft, and they then joined the coven. Among these was Evan John Jones, who would one day replace Robert Cochrane as the Magister of the Clan of Tubal Cain. Jones had met Cochrane through his wife Jane, as they both worked for the same company.<ref name=\"Roebuck\"/> The group performed their rituals either at Cochrane's house, or, more often, at [[Burnham Beeches]], though they also performed rituals at the [[South Downs]], after which they would stay the night at [[Doreen Valiente]]'s flat in [[Brighton]].<ref name=\"Roebuck\"/>\n\nIn 1966, Robert Cochrane died. Jane, Robert's widow, then named Jones as the Magister of the Clan of Tubal Cain.<ref name=\"Interview with Shani Oates\">{{cite interview |last=Oates |first=Shani |interviewer=Mike Howard |title=Shani Oates Interview |work=[[The Cauldron]], Issue 130}}</ref>\n\nIn 1982, two Americans named Dave & Ann Finnin reached out to Gray and Jones.<ref name=\"Ancient Keltic Church\">{{cite web |url=http://ancientkelticchurch.org/|title=The Ancient Keltic Church |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=<!--Not Stated--> |website=ancientkelticchurch.org |publisher=<!--Not Stated--> |access-date= 2019-07-19}}</ref> In 1986, after four years of correspondence, Jones adopted the Finnins into the Clan of Tubal Cain and named them Magister and Maid of a satellite group called The Roebuck. Conflicts later arose between Jones and the Finnians, and he ceased communications with the couple<ref name=\"Sad Wings of Destiny\">{{cite letter |title= Sad Wings of Destiny|author=Robin the Dart|url= http://www.clanoftubalcain.org.uk/luxveritatis.html |accessdate= 2019-07-19}}</ref> In 1996, Mike Howard, editor of The Cauldron, introduced Jones to a woman named Shani Oates. In 1998, Jones felt Oates to be the best person to lead the Clan of Tubal Cain and formally named her its Maid, giving her \"supreme and undivided authority over the whole Clan\".<ref name=\"Letter from Ronald Hutton\">{{cite letter |title= The Letter from Prof. Hutton, University of Bristol|first=Ronald |last=Hutton |url= http://www.clanoftubalcain.org.uk/profhutton.html |accessdate= 2019-07-19}}</ref> Oates then named as her Magister Robin the Dart. \n\nDescribing Cochrane's creation of his Witchcraft tradition, Oates remarked that \"Like any true craftsman, he was able to mold raw material into a magical [[:wikt:synthesis|synthesis]], creating a marvelous working system, at once instinctively true and intrinsically beautiful.\"<ref>[[#Oat10|Oates 2010]]. p. 228.</ref>\n\n==Beliefs==\n\n===Theology===\nAs in most forms of Neopagan Witchcraft, Cochranians worship both a [[Horned God]] and a [[Triple Goddess (Neopaganism)|Triple Goddess]]. The Goddess is viewed as the White Goddess, a term taken from [[Robert Graves]]' poem, ''[[The White Goddess]]''.<ref name=\"Roebuck\"/>  She is also viewed as a triad of three mothers or three sisters, which both Cochrane and [[Evan John Jones (Witch)|Evan John Jones]] noted as having similarities with the [[weird sisters]] or [[Norns]] of [[Germanic paganism]].<ref name=\"Roebuck\"/>\n\nIn Cochrane's Craft, the God is associated with fire, the underworld and time, and has been described as \"the goat-god of fire, craft, lower magics, fertility and death\". The God was known by several names, most notable [[Tubal-cain|Tubal Cain]], [[Br\u00e2n the Blessed|Br\u00e2n]], [[Wayland Smith|Wayland]] and [[Herne the Hunter|Herne]].<ref name=\"Roebuck\"/> Cochrane's tradition held that these two deities had a son, the Horn Child, who was a young sun god.<ref name=\"Roebuck\"/>\n\nCochrane, like Gardner, believed that there was a being beyond the God and the Goddess; the [[Deity|Godhead]], although he referred to this deity as \"the Hidden Goddess\". He also referred to it as \"Truth\".<ref name=\"Roebuck\"/>\n\nCochrane told of a [[cosmogony]] myth, which involved Night, \"a feminine being with force, but without form, giving birth to man and with him she discovered love, and so all things began\".<ref name=\"Roebuck\"/> He said that the Elder Gods had seven children who each created a realm to rule over from a castle, as well as creating the elements of earth, air, fire and water, each of which had a god ruling over it.<ref name=\"Roebuck\"/>\n\n===Ethics and morality===\nNo mention is made in Cochrane's writings to the Wiccan Rede or \"Threefold Law\". Cochrane instead offers an \"old witch 'law'\" that reads:\n\n{{quote|Do not do what you desire - do what is necessary.<br> Take all you are given - give all of yourself.<br> What I have - - - I hold!<br> When all else is lost, and not until then, prepare to die with dignity.<ref name=\"Sixth Letter to Joe Wilson\">{{cite letter |title=Sixth Letter to Joe Wilson|first=Robert |last=Cochrane |recipient=Joe Wilson |language=English |date=1966-04-08 |url= http://1734-witchcraft.org/lettersix.html|accessdate=2019-06-23 }}</ref>}}\n\nIn a letter to occultist [[William G. Gray]], Cochrane said:\n\n{{quote|Nothing is purely good or evil, these are relative terms that man has hung upon unacceptable mysteries. To my particular belief the Goddess, white with works of good, is also black with works of darkness, yet both of them are compassionate, albeit the compassion is a cover for the ruthlesness of total Truth.<ref name=\"Roebuck\"/>}}\n\n==Practices==\nCochranians wear [[robes]] whilst performing [[ritual]]s and adhere to the traditional [[Great Rite]].\n\n===Tools===\nAn iconic part of Cochrane's Craft is the tool known as the stang. A stang is a forked staff used, primarily, as a portable altar. In ''The Roebuck in the Thicket'', Evan John Johns describes the acquisition and adornment of a stang intended for use by a [[coven]]. According to Jones, the shaft of the stang should be made from ash; the fork of the stang should be made of iron; the base should be shod in iron; two upward-facing crossed arrows should adorn the shaft below the fork; and, on the four \"Great Sabbats\" (i.e. Candlemas, May Eve, Lammas, and Halloween), the arrows should be garlanded as fits the season.<ref name=\"Roebuck\"/>\n\n==Media==\nIn 2015 a feature film, ''[[The Coven (film)|The Coven]]'' was released based on the premise that \"Robbie Cochrane founded a Wicca coven as recently as the 1960s\" and that followers were meeting in [[Queen's Wood]] in [[Highgate]]. A Cochranian devotee, Uri Clef, is killed and the film's plot reveals the killer in a subtle and complex story line.\n\n==See also==\n*[[1734 Tradition]]\n*[[Folklore of the United States]]\n*[[Gardnerian Wicca]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n----\n{{WiccaandWitchcraft}}\n{{Magic and Witchcraft in the British Isles}}\n\n[[Category:Witchcraft]]\n[[Category:Modern Pagan traditions]]\n[[Category:Wicca in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox religion\n| name                = Cochrane's Craft\n| image               = \n| imagewidth          = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| abbreviation        = \n| type                = [[Traditional Witchcraft]]\n| main_classification = \n| orientation         = \n| scripture           = \n| theology            = Polytheism / Pluriform Monotheism\n| polity              = \n| governance          = \n| structure           = \n| leader_title        = \n| leader_name         =\n| leader_title1       = \n| leader_name1        = \n| leader_title2       = \n| leader_name2        = \n| fellowships_type    =\n| fellowships         = \n| fellowships_type1   =\n| fellowships1        =\n| associations        = \n| area                = \n| headquarters        = \n| founder             = Robert Cochrane (legally Roy Bowers)\n| founded_date        = 1951\n| founded_place       = \n| separated_from      = \n| parent              = \n| merger              = \n| absorbed            =\n| separations         = \n| merged_into         =\n| defunct             =\n| congregations_type  = Coven\n| congregations       =\n| members             = Unknown\n| ministers_type      = \n| ministers           = \n| missionaries        =\n| temples             =\n| hospitals           = \n| nursing_homes       = \n| aid                 = \n| primary_schools     = \n| secondary_schools   = \n| tertiary            = \n| other_names         = Cochranianism\n| publications        = \n| website             = \n| footnotes           = \n}}\n\n'''Cochrane's Craft''', which is also known as '''Cochranianism''', is a form of [[Traditional Witchcraft|traditional witchcraft]] founded in 1951 by the [[English people|English]] witch [[Robert Cochrane (witch)|Robert Cochrane]], who himself claimed to have been taught in the tradition by some of his elderly family members, a claim that is disputed by some historians such as [[Ronald Hutton]] and [[Leo Ruickbie]].<ref name=\"Roebuck\">{{cite book |last1=Cochrane |first1=Robert|last2=Jones|first2=Evan John|editor1-last=Howard|editor1-first=Mike |date= |title=Roebuck in the Thicket:An Anthology of the Robert Cochrane Witchcraft Tradition|publisher=Capall Bann|}}</ref>\n\nDespite numerous practical and theological similarities to other forms of modern witchcraft, such as Gardnerian Wicca, Cochrane's Craft sets itself apart from other traditions in many notable ways, such as its emphasis on the pursuit of wisdom as the highest goal of witchcraft<ref name=\"Second Letter to Joe Wilson\">{{cite letter |title= Second Letter to Joe Wilson|first=Robert |last=Cochrane |recipient= Joe Wilson|date= 1966-01-05|url= http://1734-witchcraft.org/lettertwo.htmlf |accessdate= 2019-06-27}}</ref> and Cochrane's insistence that witchcraft is not [[Paganism|Pagan]] and, in fact, has no more in common with Paganism than does Qabbalah.<ref name=\"Letters to Bill Grey\">{{cite letter |title= Letters to Bill Grey|first=Robert |last=Cochrane |recipient= Bill Grey|url= http://clanoftubalcain.org.uk/the_letters/letters_Bill_Gray_lk.pdf |accessdate= 2019-06-27}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nAround the time that the British [[1735 Witchcraft Act]] was repealed in 1951, and it became legal to practice [[witchcraft]] in the [[United Kingdom]], Cochrane, who was in his early twenties, founded a [[coven]], and named it the [[Clan of Tubal Cain]] after the biblical figure [[Tubal-cain]] (the first blacksmith), as a reference to his work in that profession.\n\nCochrane [[Initiation|initiated]] his wife Jane and several others into the craft, and they then joined the coven. Among these was Evan John Jones, who would one day replace Robert Cochrane as the Magister of the Clan of Tubal Cain. Jones had met Cochrane through his wife Jane, as they both worked for the same company.<ref name=\"Roebuck\"/> The group performed their rituals either at Cochrane's house, or, more often, at [[Burnham Beeches]], though they also performed rituals at the [[South Downs]], after which they would stay the night at [[Doreen Valiente]]'s flat in [[Brighton]].<ref name=\"Roebuck\"/>\n\nIn 1966, Robert Cochrane died. Jane, Robert's widow, then named Jones as the Magister of the Clan of Tubal Cain.<ref name=\"Interview with Shani Oates\">{{cite interview |last=Oates |first=Shani |interviewer=Mike Howard |title=Shani Oates Interview |work=[[The Cauldron]], Issue 130}}</ref>\n\nIn 1982, two Americans named Dave & Ann Finnin reached out to Gray and Jones.<ref name=\"Ancient Keltic Church\">{{cite web |url=http://ancientkelticchurch.org/|title=The Ancient Keltic Church |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=<!--Not Stated--> |website=ancientkelticchurch.org |publisher=<!--Not Stated--> |access-date= 2019-07-19}}</ref> In 1986, after four years of correspondence, Jones adopted the Finnins into the Clan of Tubal Cain and named them Magister and Maid of a satellite group called The Roebuck. Conflicts later arose between Jones and the Finnians, and he ceased communications with the couple<ref name=\"Sad Wings of Destiny\">{{cite letter |title= Sad Wings of Destiny|author=Robin the Dart|url= http://www.clanoftubalcain.org.uk/luxveritatis.html |accessdate= 2019-07-19}}</ref> In 1996, Mike Howard, editor of The Cauldron, introduced Jones to a woman named Shani Oates. In 1998, Jones felt Oates to be the best person to lead the Clan of Tubal Cain and formally named her its Maid, giving her \"supreme and undivided authority over the whole Clan\".<ref name=\"Letter from Ronald Hutton\">{{cite letter |title= The Letter from Prof. Hutton, University of Bristol|first=Ronald |last=Hutton |url= http://www.clanoftubalcain.org.uk/profhutton.html |accessdate= 2019-07-19}}</ref> Oates then named as her Magister Robin the Dart. \n\nDescribing Cochrane's creation of his Witchcraft tradition, Oates remarked that \"Like any true craftsman, he was able to mold raw material into a magical [[:wikt:synthesis|synthesis]], creating a marvelous working system, at once instinctively true and intrinsically beautiful.\"<ref>[[#Oat10|Oates 2010]]. p. 228.</ref>\n\n==Beliefs==\n\n===Theology===\nAs in most forms of Neopagan Witchcraft, Cochranians worship both a [[Horned God]] and a [[Triple Goddess (Neopaganism)|Triple Goddess]]. The Goddess is viewed as the White Goddess, a term taken from [[Robert Graves]]' poem, ''[[The White Goddess]]''.<ref name=\"Roebuck\"/>  She is also viewed as a triad of three mothers or three sisters, which both Cochrane and [[Evan John Jones (Witch)|Evan John Jones]] noted as having similarities with the [[weird sisters]] or [[Norns]] of [[Germanic paganism]].<ref name=\"Roebuck\"/>\n\nIn Cochrane's Craft, the God is associated with fire, the underworld and time, and has been described as \"the goat-god of fire, craft, lower magics, fertility and death\". The God was known by several names, most notable [[Tubal-cain|Tubal Cain]], [[Br\u00e2n the Blessed|Br\u00e2n]], [[Wayland Smith|Wayland]] and [[Herne the Hunter|Herne]].<ref name=\"Roebuck\"/> Cochrane's tradition held that these two deities had a son, the Horn Child, who was a young sun god.<ref name=\"Roebuck\"/>\n\nCochrane, like Gardner, believed that there was a being beyond the God and the Goddess; the [[Deity|Godhead]], although he referred to this deity as \"the Hidden Goddess\". He also referred to it as \"Truth\".<ref name=\"Roebuck\"/>\n\nCochrane told of a [[cosmogony]] myth, which involved Night, \"a feminine being with force, but without form, giving birth to man and with him she discovered love, and so all things began\".<ref name=\"Roebuck\"/> He said that the Elder Gods had seven children who each created a realm to rule over from a castle, as well as creating the elements of earth, air, fire and water, each of which had a god ruling over it.<ref name=\"Roebuck\"/>\n\n===Ethics and morality===\nNo mention is made in Cochrane's writings to the Wiccan Rede or \"Threefold Law\". Cochrane instead offers an \"old witch 'law'\" that reads:\n\n{{quote|Do not do what you desire - do what is necessary.<br> Take all you are given - give all of yourself.<br> What I have - - - I hold!<br> When all else is lost, and not until then, prepare to die with dignity.<ref name=\"Sixth Letter to Joe Wilson\">{{cite letter |title=Sixth Letter to Joe Wilson|first=Robert |last=Cochrane |recipient=Joe Wilson |language=English |date=1966-04-08 |url= http://1734-witchcraft.org/lettersix.html|accessdate=2019-06-23 }}</ref>}}\n\nIn a letter to occultist [[William G. Gray]], Cochrane said:\n\n{{quote|Nothing is purely good or evil, these are relative terms that man has hung upon unacceptable mysteries. To my particular belief the Goddess, white with works of good, is also black with works of darkness, yet both of them are compassionate, albeit the compassion is a cover for the ruthlesness of total Truth.<ref name=\"Roebuck\"/>}}\n\n==Practices==\nCochranians wear [[robes]] whilst performing [[ritual]]s and adhere to the traditional [[Great Rite]].\n\n===Tools===\nAn iconic part of Cochrane's Craft is the tool known as the stang. A stang is a forked staff used, primarily, as a portable altar. In ''The Roebuck in the Thicket'', Evan John Johns describes the acquisition and adornment of a stang intended for use by a [[coven]]. According to Jones, the shaft of the stang should be made from ash; the fork of the stang should be made of iron; the base should be shod in iron; two upward-facing crossed arrows should adorn the shaft below the fork; and, on the four \"Great Sabbats\" (i.e. Candlemas, May Eve, Lammas, and Halloween), the arrows should be garlanded as fits the season.<ref name=\"Roebuck\"/>\n\n==Media==\nIn 2015 a feature film, ''[[The Coven (film)|The Coven]]'' was released based on the premise that \"Robbie Cochrane founded a Wicca coven as recently as the 1960s\" and that followers were meeting in [[Queen's Wood]] in [[Highgate]]. A Cochranian devotee, Uri Clef, is killed and the film's plot reveals the killer in a subtle and complex story line.\n\n==See also==\n*[[1734 Tradition]]\n*[[Folklore of the United States]]\n*[[Gardnerian Wicca]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n----\n{{WiccaandWitchcraft}}\n{{Magic and Witchcraft in the British Isles}}\n\n[[Category:Witchcraft]]\n[[Category:Modern Pagan traditions]]\n[[Category:Wicca in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Wbm1058", "label": "safe", "comment": "miscapitalization", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cochrane%27s_Craft"}
{"title_page": "Bent Flyvbjerg", "text_new": "{{short description|Danish economic geographer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n'''Bent Flyvbjerg''' is a Danish economic geographer. He is Professor of Major Programme Management at [[Oxford University]]'s [[Sa\u00efd Business School]] and the first Director of the University's [[BT Group|BT]] Centre for Major Programme Management. He was previously Professor of Planning at [[Aalborg University]], [[Denmark]] and Chair of Infrastructure Policy and Planning at [[Delft University of Technology]], The Netherlands.<ref>Krak's Who's Who, Copenhagen, 2008</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.sbs.ox.ac.uk/community/people/bent-flyvbjerg|title=Bent Flyvbjerg|last=|first=|date=|website=Said Business School, University of Oxford|publisher=|access-date=2016-04-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180412151811/https://www.sbs.ox.ac.uk/community/people/bent-flyvbjerg|archive-date=2018-04-12|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref>  He is a fellow of [[St Anne's College, Oxford]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ox.ac.uk/news-and-events/find-an-expert/professor-bent-flyvbjerg|title=Professor Bent Flyvbjerg - University of Oxford|website=www.ox.ac.uk}}</ref>\n\n== Academic Work ==\nFlyvbjerg is the author or editor of 10 books and more than 200 papers in professional journals and edited volumes. His publications have been translated into 20 languages. His research has been covered by Science, The Economist, The New York Times, The Wall Street Journal, The Financial Times, China Daily, The BBC, CNN, and many other media.<ref name=\":0\" /> He is a frequent commentator in the media.\n\nFlyvbjerg received his Ph.D. in [[urban geography]] and planning from [[Aarhus University]], Denmark, with parts done at the [[University of California, Los Angeles|University of California at Los Angeles]]. He has written extensively about [[megaprojects]], [[decision making]], [[city management]], and [[philosophy of social science]]. He was a member of the Danish Infrastructure Commission and a director of the Danish Court Administration.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Infrastrukturkommissionens bet\u00e6nkning - Transportministeriet|url = http://www.trm.dk/da/publikationer/2008/infrastrukturkommissionens-betaenkning|website = www.trm.dk|accessdate = 2015-12-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=December 2003|title=Med en \"bestyrers\" \u00f8jne|url=https://www.domstol.dk/om/publikationer/HtmlPublikationer/Danmarks%20Domstole/Danmarks%20Domstole%20nr.%2020/kap06.htm|journal=Danmarks Domstole, No. 20|doi=|pmid=|access-date=2016-04-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304091021/https://www.domstol.dk/om/publikationer/HtmlPublikationer/Danmarks%20Domstole/Danmarks%20Domstole%20nr.%2020/kap06.htm|archive-date=2016-03-04|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> He has twice held the [[Fulbright Program|Fulbright]] Scholarship. Bent Flyvbjerg was [[knight]]ed in the [[Order of the Dannebrog]] in 2002.\n\nHis research falls in three main areas: (a) The philosophy and methodology of the social sciences, (b) Power and rationality in decision making, and (c) Megaproject planning and management.\n\nIn the philosophy and methodology of the social sciences, Flyvbjerg's main contribution is developing the theory and methodology of phronetic social science, i.e., a social science based on [[Aristotelian ethics|Aristotelian]] [[phronesis]]. Flyvbjerg argues that social sciences that attempt to emulate [[natural science]] and predictive theory have failed, and will continue to fail. He further argues that in order to matter the social sciences must inform [[practical reason]] instead of abstract [[rationality]]. This is best done by a focus on values and power in actual human decision making, according to Flyvbjerg. He develops the methodological guidelines for such research and demonstrates how to employ them in concrete case studies in phronetic social science. Phronetic research is aimed at being directly relevant to society and people, including ordinary citizens and policy makers. In terms of philosophy and history of science, Flyvbjerg is influenced by Aristotle rather than by Socrates and Plato. Flyvbjerg's key works on phronetic social science are the books ''[[Making Social Science Matter|Making Social Science Matter: Why Social Inquiry Fails and How It Can Succeed Again]]<ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, 2001, ''Making Social Science Matter: Why Social Inquiry Fails and How It Can Succeed Again'' (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press), 214 pp.</ref>'' and ''[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=3I2fBeHZpBcC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Real+Social+Science:+Applied+Phronesis&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjzpvjL4eroAhWOYcAKHcWsAUoQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=Real%20Social%20Science%3A%20Applied%20Phronesis&f=false Real Social Science: Applied Phronesis]'' (with Sanford Schram and Todd Landman),<ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, Todd Landman, and Sanford Schram, 2012 eds., ''Real Social Science: Applied Phronesis'' (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press), 319 pp.</ref> both published by [[Cambridge University Press]], plus a number of research papers.<ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, 2004, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2278320 Phronetic Planning Research: Theoretical and Methodological Reflections].\" ''Planning Theory and Practice'' , vol. 5, no. 3, September, pp. 283-306.</ref> <ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, 2002, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2278388 Bringing Power to Planning Research: One Researcher\u2019s Praxis Story].\" Invited plenary paper for ''Planning Research 2000'', London School of Economics and Political Science, 27-29 March 2000. ''Journal of Planning Education and Research'', vol. 21, no. 4, Summer 2002, pp. 353-366. </ref> <ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, 2004, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2278337 A Perestroikan Straw Man Answers Back: David Laitin and Phronetic Political Science],\" ''Politics and Society'', vol. 32, no. 3, September, pp. 389-416. </ref> <ref>Schram, Sanford F., Bent Flyvbjerg, and Todd Landman, 2013, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2309929 ''Political'' Political Science: A Phronetic Approach],\" ''New Political Science'', vol. 35, no. 3, pp. 359-372, DOI:10.1080/07393148.2013.813687</ref> <ref>Clegg, Stewart, Bent Flyvbjerg, and Mark Haugaard, 2014, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2460651 Reflections on Phronetic Social Science: A Dialogue Between Stewart Clegg, Bent Flyvbjerg, and Mark Haugaard],\" ''Journal of Political Power'', June, pp. 1-32, DOI: 10.1080/2158379X.2014.929259</ref> Flyvbjerg's work has been extensively debated in the social sciences, most prominently in the so-called \"Flyvbjerg Debate\" covered in the book ''[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=kyJ5GJ7DeMQC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Making+Political+Science+Matter:+Debating+Knowledge,+Research,+and+Method&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiIlazs4eroAhWmaRUIHVBNAG0Q6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=Making%20Political%20Science%20Matter%3A%20Debating%20Knowledge%2C%20Research%2C%20and%20Method&f=false Making Political Science Matter: Debating Knowledge, Research, and Method]'', edited by Sanford Schram and Brian Caterino.<ref>Schram, Sanford F. and Brian Caterino, 2006 eds., ''Making Political Science Matter: Debating Knowledge, Research, and Method'' (New York: New York University Press).</ref>\n\nIn his research on power and rationality, Flyvbjerg has documented how power influences rationality, and vice versa. Flyvbjerg here shows that in human decision making what is called rationality often turns out to be rationalization, under the influence of power. Flyvbjerg sums up this work in a number of propositions about power and rationality, among which:\n\n* Power defines reality;\n* Rationality is context-dependent; the context of rationality is power;\n* Rationalization presented as rationality is a principal strategy in the exercize of power;\n* The greater the power, the less the rationality;\n* Power has a rationality that rationality does not know.\n\nFlyvbjerg argues that his research on power and rationality is an instance of phronetic social science (see above).<ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, 2001, Making Social Science Matter: Why Social Inquiry Fails and How It Can Succeed Again, translator Steven Sampson (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press), pp. 144 ff.</ref> Theoretically and methodologically, the main influences on Flyvbjerg's work on power and rationality are [[Thucydides]], [[Niccol\u00f2 Machiavelli|Machiavelli]], and [[Friedrich Nietzsche|Nietzsche]]. Flyvbjerg specifically highlights Machiavelli's power studies in Florence as a source of influence for the choice of in-depth case studies as the means for understanding the dynamics of power and how power enables and constrains rationality and rational government. Flyvbjerg's main works on power and rationality are the book ''[[Rationality and Power|Rationality and Power: Democracy in Practice]],''<ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, 1998, ''Rationality and Power: Democracy in Practice'' (Chicago: The University of Chicago Press). </ref> published by the [[University of Chicago Press]], plus a number of research papers.<ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, 2002, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2278388 Bringing Power to Planning Research: One Researcher\u2019s Praxis Story].\" Invited plenary paper for ''Planning Research 2000'', London School of Economics and Political Science, 27-29 March 2000. ''Journal of Planning Education and Research'', vol. 21, no. 4, Summer 2002, pp. 353-366. </ref> <ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, 1998, \u201c[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2237923 Habermas and Foucault: Thinkers for Civil Society]?\u201d ''British Journal of Sociology'', vol. 49, no. 2, June, pp. 208-233.</ref> <ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, 1996, \u201c[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2278431 The Dark Side of Planning: Rationality and ''Realrationalit\u00e4t'']'',''\u201d in Seymour Mandelbaum, Luigi Mazza, and Robert Burchell, eds., ''Explorations in Planning Theory'' (New Brunswick, NJ: Center for Urban Policy Research Press) pp. 383-394.</ref> <ref>Bent Flyvbjerg, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2278418 Beyond the Limits of Planning Theory: Response to My Critics].\" ''International Planning Studies'', vol. 6, no. 3, August 2001, pp. 285-292. </ref> <ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, 2015, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2536476 More on the Dark Side of Planning: Response to Richard Bolan],\" ''Cities'', vol. 42, February, pp. 276\u2013278.</ref> <ref>Bent Flyvbjerg, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2230464 Five Misunderstandings About Case Study Research].\" ''Qualitative Inquiry'', vol. 12, no. 2, April 2006, pp. 219-245.</ref> <ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent and Tim Richardson, 2002, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2278389 Planning and Foucault: In Search of the Dark Side of Planning Theory],\" in Philip Allmendinger and Mark Tewdwr-Jones, eds., ''Planning Futures: New Directions for Planning Theory'' (London and New York: Routledge), pp. 44-62.</ref>\n\nFlyvbjerg's research on [[megaproject]] planning and management compares plans with actual outcomes, and explains discrepancies. Flyvbjerg documents what he calls [https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2742088 The Iron Law of Megaprojects]: \"Over time, over budget, under benefits, over and over again.\"<ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, 2017, \"Introduction: The Iron Law of Megaproject Management\", in Bent Flyvbjerg, ed., ''The Oxford Handbook of Megaproject Management'' (Oxford: Oxford University Press), pp. 1-18.</ref> This is a statistical, not a deterministic, law. Megaprojects that are on time, budget, and benefits do exist, but they are rare, according to the data. The Iron Law applies at an overwhelmingly high level of statistical significance. Flyvbjerg shows that a root cause is that competition between megaprojects and their sponsors creates biases rooted in political and organizational pressures that lead to the consistent overestimating of project benefits and the underestimating of project costs. The best megaprojects do not get implemented, but rather the ones that look best on paper. Flyvbjerg argues that the ones that look best on paper are the ones for which costs and benefits have been misrepresented the most, either deliberately through strategic misrepresentation (political bias), or non-deliberately through [[optimism bias]] (psychological bias) or, typically, through a combination of both. \n\nFlyvbjerg identifies three antidotes to the Iron Law: (a) Realistic planning, including de-biasing of all cost, schedule, and benefit estimates; (b) High-quality delivery teams; and (c) Governance structures with incentives for realistic plans and for delivering those plans to time, budget, and benefits; and with early-warning-sign systems to immediately capture and act on things that go wrong, which they invariably do in megaprojects, due to their sheer size and complexity, according to Flyvbjerg. Based on [[Daniel Kahneman|Daniel Kahneman's]] work on the [[planning fallacy]] and optimism bias, Flyvbjerg pioneered [[reference class forecasting]] as a practical method for de-biasing megaproject plans. In his book, [[Thinking, Fast and Slow|''Thinking, Fast and Slow'']], Kahneman calls Flyvbjerg's insights on the planning fallacy and reference class forecasting, \"the single most important piece of advice regarding how to increase accuracy in forecasting.\"<ref>Kahneman, Daniel, 2011, ''Thinking, Fast and Slow'' (New York: Farrar, Straus and Giroux), p. 251.</ref> Daniel Kahneman is a key intellectual influence for Flyvbjerg's work on megaprojects, as is [[Nassim Nicholas Taleb]], especially his work on [[Black swan statistics|black swans]], and [[Martin Wachs]], who was Flyvbjerg's doctoral supervisor at UCLA. Flyvbjerg's key works on megaproject planning and management are the books ''[[Megaprojects and Risk|Megaprojects and Risk: An Anatomy of Ambition]]'' (with Nils Bruzelius and Werner Rothengatter),<ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, Nils Bruzelius, and Werner Rothengatter, 2003, ''Megaprojects and Risk: An Anatomy of Ambition'' (Cambridge University Press). </ref> ''[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=5kupDgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=The+Oxford+Handbook+of+Megaproject+Management&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjM3omh4uroAhWAQxUIHQfRCaUQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q&f=false The Oxford Handbook of Megaproject Management]'',<ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, 2017, ed., ''The Oxford Handbook of Megaproject Management'' (Oxford: Oxford University Press).</ref> ''[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=tenILJ-MowQC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Decision-Making+On+Mega-Projects:+Cost\u2013benefit+Analysis,+Planning,+and+Innovation&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiLgqC84uroAhUyQRUIHXLbDUsQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q&f=false Decision-Making On Mega-Projects: Cost\u2013benefit Analysis, Planning, and Innovation]'' (with Hugo Priemus and Bert van Wee),<ref>Priemus, Hugo, Bent Flyvbjerg, and Bert van Wee, 2008, eds., ''Decision-Making On Mega-Projects: Cost\u2013benefit Analysis, Planning, and Innovation'' (Cheltenham, UK and Northampton, MA, USA: Edward Elgar).</ref> and ''Megaproject Planning and Management: Essential Readings'',<ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, 2014, ed., ''Megaproject Planning and Management: Essential Readings'', vols. I-II (Cheltenham, UK and Northampton, MA: Edward Elgar).</ref> plus a number of research papers.<ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, 2016, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2767128 The Fallacy of Beneficial Ignorance: A Test of Hirschman's Hiding Hand],\" ''World Development'', vol. 84, May, pp. 176\u2013189. http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.worlddev.2016.03.012.</ref> <ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, 2014, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2424835 What You Should Know about Megaprojects and Why: An Overview],\" ''Project Management Journal'', vol. 45, no. 2, April-May, pp. 6-19. </ref> <ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, 2013, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2229700 Quality Control and Due Diligence in Project Management: Getting Decisions Right by Taking the Outside View],\" ''International Journal of Project Management'', vol. 31, no. 5, May, pp. 760\u2013774. DOI: 10.1016/j.ijproman.2012.10.007</ref> <ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, 2013, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2278887 How Planners Deal with Uncomfortable Knowledge: The Dubious Ethics of the American Planning Association],\" ''Cities'', vol. 32, June, pp. 157\u2013163.</ref><ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, 2006, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2238013 From Nobel Prize to Project Management: Getting Risks Right],\" ''Project Management Journal'', vol. 37, no. 3, August, pp. 5-15.</ref> <ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, and J. Rodney Turner, 2018, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=3012134 Do Classics Exist in Megaproject Management]?\", ''International Journal of Project Management'', vol. 36, no. 2, pp. 334-341, DOI: 10.1016/j.ijproman.2017.07.006. </ref> <ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, Allison Stewart, and Alexander Budzier, 2016, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2804554 The Oxford Olympics Study 2016: Cost and Cost Overrun at the Games],\" ''Sa\u00efd Business School Working Papers'' (Oxford: University of Oxford), July.</ref> <ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent and Alexander Budzier, 2011, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2229735 Why Your IT Project May Be Riskier than You Think],\" ''Harvard Business Review'', September, pp. 601-603.</ref> <ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, Massimo Garbuio''',''' and Dan Lovallo, 2009, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2229781 Delusion and Deception in Large Infrastructure Projects: Two Models for Explaining and Preventing Executive Disaster],\" ''California Management Review'', vol. 51, no. 2, Winter, pp. 170-193.</ref> <ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, Mette K. Skamris Holm, and S\u00f8ren L. Buhl, 2005, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2238050 How (In)accurate Are Demand Forecasts in Public Works Projects? The Case of Transportation].\" ''Journal of the American Planning Association'', vol. 71, no. 2, Spring, pp. 131-146. </ref> <ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, Mette K. Skamris Holm, and S\u00f8ren L. Buhl, 2002, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2278415 Underestimating Costs in Public Works Projects: Error or Lie]?\" ''Journal of the American Planning Association'', vol. 68, no. 3, Summer, pp. 279-295.</ref> <ref>Atif Ansar, Bent Flyvbjerg, Alexander Budzier, and Daniel Lunn, 2016, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2834326 Does Infrastructure Investment Lead to Economic Growth or Economic Fragility? Evidence from China],\" ''Oxford Review of Economic Policy'', vol. 32, no. 3, autumn, pp. 360\u2013390; DOI: 10.1093/oxrep/grw022</ref> <ref>Ansar, Atif, Bent Flyvbjerg, Alexander Budzier, and Daniel Lunn, 2014, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2406852 Should We Build More Large Dams? The Actual Costs of Hydropower Megaproject Development],\" ''Energy Policy'', vol. 69, March, pp. 43-56.</ref> Flyvbjerg has argued that his work on megaprojects constitutes an example of phronetic social science (see above).<ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, 2012, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2278219 Why Mass Media Matter and How to Work with Them: Phronesis and Megaprojects],\" in Bent Flyvbjerg, Todd Landman, and Sanford Schram, eds., ''Real Social Science: Applied Phronesis'' (Cambridge University Press), pp. 95-121.</ref>\n\n== Oxford BT Professorship in Major Programme Management ==\nIn 2007, [[BT Group]] (formerly British Telecom) donated funds to [[University of Oxford|the University of Oxford]] to set up permanently the [[List of professorships at the University of Oxford|BT Professorship and Chair in Major Programme Management]]. In 2008, Oxford University headhunted Bent Flyvbjerg for the position from Aalborg and Delft. Flyvbjerg is Oxford University's first BT Professor and inaugural Chair of Major Programme Management.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbs.ox.ac.uk/about-us/people/bent-flyvbjerg|title=Bent Flyvbjerg's Oxford University website|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Readership ==\nBent Flyvbjerg's publications are widely read and cited. [[Making Social Science Matter: Why Social Inquiry Fails and How It Can Succeed Again|His book ''Making Social Social Science Matter'': ''Why Social Inquiry Fails and How It Can Succeed Again'']] has more than 7,000 citations at [https://scholar.google.com/citations?hl=en&user=79htA7gAAAAJ&pagesize=100&view_op=list_works#d=gs_md_cita-d&u=%2Fcitations%3Fview_op%3Dview_citation%26hl%3Den%26user%3D79htA7gAAAAJ%26pagesize%3D100%26citation_for_view%3D79htA7gAAAAJ%3Au5HHmVD_uO8C%26tzom%3D0 Google Scholar], making it the most cited current book in the philosophy and methodology of social science. ''[[Megaprojects and Risk: An Anatomy of Ambition|Megaprojects and Risk. An Anatomy of Ambition]]'' has more than [https://scholar.google.com/citations?hl=en&user=79htA7gAAAAJ&pagesize=100&view_op=list_works#d=gs_md_cita-d&u=%2Fcitations%3Fview_op%3Dview_citation%26hl%3Den%26user%3D79htA7gAAAAJ%26pagesize%3D100%26citation_for_view%3D79htA7gAAAAJ%3A9yKSN-GCB0IC%26tzom%3D0 3,500 citations], making it the most cited book on megaproject planning and management. ''[[Rationality and Power: Democracy in Practice]]'' has more than [https://scholar.google.com/citations?hl=en&user=79htA7gAAAAJ&pagesize=100&view_op=list_works#d=gs_md_cita-d&u=%2Fcitations%3Fview_op%3Dview_citation%26hl%3Den%26user%3D79htA7gAAAAJ%26pagesize%3D100%26citation_for_view%3D79htA7gAAAAJ%3Ad1gkVwhDpl0C%26tzom%3D0 2,900 citations], making it one of the most cited books in city planning and management and winning Flyvbjerg the nomination of \"[https://www.amazon.com/Key-Thinkers-Cities-Regan-Koch/dp/1473907756/ref=sr_1_1?crid=1V2Y6G2U9Y2C1&keywords=key+thinkers+on+cities&qid=1581598403&sprefix=key+thinkers+on+cities%2Caps%2C237&sr=8-1 Key Thinker on Cities].\" Flyvbjerg's classic paper, \"Five Misunderstandings about Case-Study Research,\" has more than [https://scholar.google.com/citations?hl=en&user=79htA7gAAAAJ&pagesize=100&view_op=list_works#d=gs_md_cita-d&u=%2Fcitations%3Fview_op%3Dview_citation%26hl%3Den%26user%3D79htA7gAAAAJ%26pagesize%3D100%26citation_for_view%3D79htA7gAAAAJ%3Au-x6o8ySG0sC%26tzom%3D0 14,000 citations] at Google Scholar.\n\n== Honors and Awards ==\n\n* [https://www.pmi.org/about/awards/research-academic/research-achievement Project Management Institute Research Achievement Award], which \"recognizes and honors an individual whose work has significantly advanced the concepts, knowledge, and practices of project management through a published body of academic research,\" 2019.\n* [https://www.eiasm.net/about_eiasm/interdisciplinary-leader-award EIASM Interdisciplinary Leader Award], conferred by the Board of The European Institute for Advanced Studies in Management for \"exemplary contributions in interdisciplinary research,\" 2017.\n* [https://www.emeraldgrouppublishing.com/about/news/story.htm?id=3548 Emerald Citation of Excellence Award], in recognition of the paper \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2424835 What You Should Know about Megaprojects and Why: An Overview],\" ''Project Management Journal'', vol. 45, \"as one of the most highly cited and highly influential papers,\" 2017.\n* [https://www.pmi.org/about/awards/research-academic/pm-journal-paper-of-the-year Paper of the Year Award], conferred by the Project Management Institute and Project Management Journal for the paper \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2424835 What You Should Know about Megaprojects and Why: An Overview],\" ''Project Management Journal'', vol. 45, 2015.\n* [https://www.apm.org.uk/about-us/how-apm-is-run/honorary-fellows/ Honorary Fellow of the Association for Project Management], awarded for \"outstanding contributions to project management,\" 2011.\n* [http://www.aesop-planning.eu/en_GB/awards Association of European Schools of Planning's Best Published Paper Prize], awarded for the paper \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2230414 Policy and Planning for Large Infrastructure Projects: Problems, Causes, Cures],\" ''Environment and Planning B'', vol. 34, 2008.\n* [https://www.cies.org Fulbright Scholar], twice, awarded by the Fulbright Commission, Washington, DC.\n* [http://www.amscan.org Honorary Fellow under the American-Scandinavian Foundation].\n* [http://kongehuset.dk/en/the-monarchy-in-denmark/the-royal-symbols/the-royal-orders-of-chivalry Knighthood of the Order of the Dannebrog], awarded by Queen Margrethe II of Denmark for professional accomplishments, 2002.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.linkedin.com/in/flyvbjerg/|title=Full list of honors and awards for Bent Flyvbjerg.|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Advisory Work ==\nBent Flyvbjerg is co-founder and Chairman of [https://www.oxfordglobalprojects.com Oxford Global Projects]. He has advised government and business, including the US, UK, and Chinese governments and Fortune 500 companies. He also serves as external advisor to McKinsey & Co.\n\n==Books==\n*1998 ''[[Rationality and Power: Democracy in Practice]]'', University of Chicago Press ({{ISBN|0226254518}})\n*2001 ''[[Making Social Science Matter: Why Social Inquiry Fails and How It Can Succeed Again]]'', Cambridge University Press ({{ISBN|0-521-77568-X}})\n*2003 ''[[Megaprojects and Risk: An Anatomy of Ambition]]''. Cambridge University Press ({{ISBN|0-521-00946-4}})\n*2008 ''[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=tenILJ-MowQC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Decision-Making+on+Mega-Projects:+Cost-Benefit+Analysis,+Planning+and+Innovation&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwilv7uoq8_nAhVSilwKHT_jBPAQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=Decision-Making%20on%20Mega-Projects%3A%20Cost-Benefit%20Analysis%2C%20Planning%20and%20Innovation&f=false Decision-Making on Mega-Projects: Cost-Benefit Analysis, Planning and Innovation]'', Elgar ({{ISBN|978-1-84542-737-5}})\n*2012 [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=3I2fBeHZpBcC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Real+Social+Science:+Applied+Phronesis,+Cambridge+University+Press&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwib_rfHq8_nAhVGQ8AKHS4wCNcQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=Real%20Social%20Science%3A%20Applied%20Phronesis%2C%20Cambridge%20University%20Press&f=false ''Real Social Science: Applied Phronesis'', Cambridge University Press] ({{ISBN|978-0-521-16820-5}})\n*2014 ''[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=zOQhvgAACAAJ&dq=editions%3AQg6umPDRoXwC&source=gbs_book_other_versions Megaproject Planning and Management: Essential Readings, Volumes I-II]'', Elgar ({{ISBN|978-1-78100-170-7}})\n*2017 ''[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=J_8lDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=The+Oxford+Handbook+of+Megaproject+Management&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjGoviQrM_nAhXBkFwKHe8HDL4Q6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=The%20Oxford%20Handbook%20of%20Megaproject%20Management&f=false The Oxford Handbook of Megaproject Management]'', Oxford University Press ({{ISBN|978-0-19873-224-2}})\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Flyvbjerg, Bent}}\n[[Category:Danish urban planners]]\n[[Category:Delft University of Technology faculty]]\n[[Category:Danish geographers]]\n[[Category:Statutory Professors of the University of Oxford]]\n[[Category:Dutch urban planners]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Philosophers of social science]]\n[[Category:Academics of Sa\u00efd Business School]]\n[[Category:People associated with Aalborg University]]\n[[Category:Fulbright Scholars]]\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Danish economic geographer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n'''Bent Flyvbjerg''' is a Danish economic geographer. He is Professor of Major Programme Management at [[Oxford University]]'s [[Sa\u00efd Business School]] and the first Director of the University's [[BT Group|BT]] Centre for Major Programme Management. He was previously Professor of Planning at [[Aalborg University]], [[Denmark]] and Chair of Infrastructure Policy and Planning at [[Delft University of Technology]], The Netherlands.<ref>Krak's Who's Who, Copenhagen, 2008</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.sbs.ox.ac.uk/community/people/bent-flyvbjerg|title=Bent Flyvbjerg|last=|first=|date=|website=Said Business School, University of Oxford|publisher=|access-date=2016-04-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180412151811/https://www.sbs.ox.ac.uk/community/people/bent-flyvbjerg|archive-date=2018-04-12|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref>  He is a fellow of [[St Anne's College, Oxford]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ox.ac.uk/news-and-events/find-an-expert/professor-bent-flyvbjerg|title=Professor Bent Flyvbjerg - University of Oxford|website=www.ox.ac.uk}}</ref>\n\n== Academic Work ==\nFlyvbjerg is the author or editor of 10 books and more than 200 papers in professional journals and edited volumes. His publications have been translated into 20 languages. His research has been covered by Science, The Economist, The New York Times, The Wall Street Journal, The Financial Times, China Daily, The BBC, CNN, and many other media.<ref name=\":0\" /> He is a frequent commentator in the media.\n\nFlyvbjerg received his Ph.D. in [[urban geography]] and planning from [[Aarhus University]], Denmark, with parts done at the [[University of California, Los Angeles|University of California at Los Angeles]]. He has written extensively about [[megaprojects]], [[decision making]], [[city management]], and [[philosophy of social science]]. He was a member of the Danish Infrastructure Commission and a director of the Danish Court Administration.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Infrastrukturkommissionens bet\u00e6nkning - Transportministeriet|url = http://www.trm.dk/da/publikationer/2008/infrastrukturkommissionens-betaenkning|website = www.trm.dk|accessdate = 2015-12-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=December 2003|title=Med en \"bestyrers\" \u00f8jne|url=https://www.domstol.dk/om/publikationer/HtmlPublikationer/Danmarks%20Domstole/Danmarks%20Domstole%20nr.%2020/kap06.htm|journal=Danmarks Domstole, No. 20|doi=|pmid=|access-date=2016-04-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304091021/https://www.domstol.dk/om/publikationer/HtmlPublikationer/Danmarks%20Domstole/Danmarks%20Domstole%20nr.%2020/kap06.htm|archive-date=2016-03-04|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> He has twice held the [[Fulbright Program|Fulbright]] Scholarship. Bent Flyvbjerg was [[knight]]ed in the [[Order of the Dannebrog]] in 2002.\n\nHis research falls in three main areas: (a) The philosophy and methodology of the social sciences, (b) Power and rationality in decision making, and (c) Megaproject planning and management.\n\nIn the philosophy and methodology of the social sciences, Flyvbjerg's main contribution is developing the theory and methodology of phronetic social science, i.e., a social science based on [[Aristotelian ethics|Aristotelian]] [[phronesis]]. Flyvbjerg argues that social sciences that attempt to emulate [[natural science]] and predictive theory have failed, and will continue to fail. He further argues that in order to matter the social sciences must inform [[practical reason]] instead of abstract [[rationality]]. This is best done by a focus on values and power in actual human decision making, according to Flyvbjerg. He develops the methodological guidelines for such research and demonstrates how to employ them in concrete case studies in phronetic social science. Phronetic research is aimed at being directly relevant to society and people, including ordinary citizens and policy makers. In terms of philosophy and history of science, Flyvbjerg is influenced by Aristotle rather than by Socrates and Plato. Flyvbjerg's key works on phronetic social science are the books ''[[Making Social Science Matter|Making Social Science Matter: Why Social Inquiry Fails and How It Can Succeed Again]]<ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, 2001, ''Making Social Science Matter: Why Social Inquiry Fails and How It Can Succeed Again'' (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press), 214 pp.</ref>'' and ''[[Real Social Science: Applied Phronesis]]'' (with Sanford Schram and Todd Landman),<ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, Todd Landman, and Sanford Schram, 2012 eds., ''Real Social Science: Applied Phronesis'' (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press), 319 pp.</ref> both published by [[Cambridge University Press]], plus a number of research papers.<ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, 2004, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2278320 Phronetic Planning Research: Theoretical and Methodological Reflections].\" ''Planning Theory and Practice'' , vol. 5, no. 3, September, pp. 283-306.</ref> <ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, 2002, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2278388 Bringing Power to Planning Research: One Researcher\u2019s Praxis Story].\" Invited plenary paper for ''Planning Research 2000'', London School of Economics and Political Science, 27-29 March 2000. ''Journal of Planning Education and Research'', vol. 21, no. 4, Summer 2002, pp. 353-366. </ref> <ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, 2004, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2278337 A Perestroikan Straw Man Answers Back: David Laitin and Phronetic Political Science],\" ''Politics and Society'', vol. 32, no. 3, September, pp. 389-416. </ref> <ref>Schram, Sanford F., Bent Flyvbjerg, and Todd Landman, 2013, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2309929 ''Political'' Political Science: A Phronetic Approach],\" ''New Political Science'', vol. 35, no. 3, pp. 359-372, DOI:10.1080/07393148.2013.813687</ref> <ref>Clegg, Stewart, Bent Flyvbjerg, and Mark Haugaard, 2014, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2460651 Reflections on Phronetic Social Science: A Dialogue Between Stewart Clegg, Bent Flyvbjerg, and Mark Haugaard],\" ''Journal of Political Power'', June, pp. 1-32, DOI: 10.1080/2158379X.2014.929259</ref> Flyvbjerg's work has been extensively debated in the social sciences, most prominently in the so-called \"Flyvbjerg Debate\" covered in the book ''[[Making Political Science Matter: Debating Knowledge, Research, and Method]]'', edited by Sanford Schram and Brian Caterino.<ref>Schram, Sanford F. and Brian Caterino, 2006 eds., ''Making Political Science Matter: Debating Knowledge, Research, and Method'' (New York: New York University Press).</ref>\n\nIn his research on power and rationality, Flyvbjerg has documented how power influences rationality, and vice versa. Flyvbjerg here shows that in human decision making what is called rationality often turns out to be rationalization, under the influence of power. Flyvbjerg sums up this work in a number of propositions about power and rationality, among which:\n\n* Power defines reality;\n* Rationality is context-dependent; the context of rationality is power;\n* Rationalization presented as rationality is a principal strategy in the exercize of power;\n* The greater the power, the less the rationality;\n* Power has a rationality that rationality does not know.\n\nFlyvbjerg argues that his research on power and rationality is an instance of phronetic social science (see above).<ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, 2001, Making Social Science Matter: Why Social Inquiry Fails and How It Can Succeed Again, translator Steven Sampson (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press), pp. 144 ff.</ref> Theoretically and methodologically, the main influences on Flyvbjerg's work on power and rationality are [[Thucydides]], [[Niccol\u00f2 Machiavelli|Machiavelli]], and [[Friedrich Nietzsche|Nietzsche]]. Flyvbjerg specifically highlights Machiavelli's power studies in Florence as a source of influence for the choice of in-depth case studies as the means for understanding the dynamics of power and how power enables and constrains rationality and rational government. Flyvbjerg's main works on power and rationality are the book ''[[Rationality and Power|Rationality and Power: Democracy in Practice]],''<ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, 1998, ''Rationality and Power: Democracy in Practice'' (Chicago: The University of Chicago Press). </ref> published by the [[University of Chicago Press]], plus a number of research papers.<ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, 2002, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2278388 Bringing Power to Planning Research: One Researcher\u2019s Praxis Story].\" Invited plenary paper for ''Planning Research 2000'', London School of Economics and Political Science, 27-29 March 2000. ''Journal of Planning Education and Research'', vol. 21, no. 4, Summer 2002, pp. 353-366. </ref> <ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, 1998, \u201c[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2237923 Habermas and Foucault: Thinkers for Civil Society]?\u201d ''British Journal of Sociology'', vol. 49, no. 2, June, pp. 208-233.</ref> <ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, 1996, \u201c[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2278431 The Dark Side of Planning: Rationality and ''Realrationalit\u00e4t'']'',''\u201d in Seymour Mandelbaum, Luigi Mazza, and Robert Burchell, eds., ''Explorations in Planning Theory'' (New Brunswick, NJ: Center for Urban Policy Research Press) pp. 383-394.</ref> <ref>Bent Flyvbjerg, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2278418 Beyond the Limits of Planning Theory: Response to My Critics].\" ''International Planning Studies'', vol. 6, no. 3, August 2001, pp. 285-292. </ref> <ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, 2015, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2536476 More on the Dark Side of Planning: Response to Richard Bolan],\" ''Cities'', vol. 42, February, pp. 276\u2013278.</ref> <ref>Bent Flyvbjerg, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2230464 Five Misunderstandings About Case Study Research].\" ''Qualitative Inquiry'', vol. 12, no. 2, April 2006, pp. 219-245.</ref> <ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent and Tim Richardson, 2002, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2278389 Planning and Foucault: In Search of the Dark Side of Planning Theory],\" in Philip Allmendinger and Mark Tewdwr-Jones, eds., ''Planning Futures: New Directions for Planning Theory'' (London and New York: Routledge), pp. 44-62.</ref>\n\nFlyvbjerg's research on [[megaproject]] planning and management compares plans with actual outcomes, and explains discrepancies. Flyvbjerg documents what he calls [[The Iron Law of Megaprojects]]: \"Over time, over budget, under benefits, over and over again.\"<ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, 2017, \"Introduction: The Iron Law of Megaproject Management\", in Bent Flyvbjerg, ed., ''The Oxford Handbook of Megaproject Management'' (Oxford: Oxford University Press), pp. 1-18.</ref> This is a statistical, not a deterministic, law. Megaprojects that are on time, budget, and benefits do exist, but they are rare, according to the data. The Iron Law applies at an overwhelmingly high level of statistical significance. Flyvbjerg shows that a root cause is that competition between megaprojects and their sponsors creates biases rooted in political and organizational pressures that lead to the consistent overestimating of project benefits and the underestimating of project costs. The best megaprojects do not get implemented, but rather the ones that look best on paper. Flyvbjerg argues that the ones that look best on paper are the ones for which costs and benefits have been misrepresented the most, either deliberately through strategic misrepresentation (political bias), or non-deliberately through [[optimism bias]] (psychological bias) or, typically, through a combination of both. \n\nFlyvbjerg identifies three antidotes to the Iron Law: (a) Realistic planning, including de-biasing of all cost, schedule, and benefit estimates; (b) High-quality delivery teams; and (c) Governance structures with incentives for realistic plans and for delivering those plans to time, budget, and benefits; and with early-warning-sign systems to immediately capture and act on things that go wrong, which they invariably do in megaprojects, due to their sheer size and complexity, according to Flyvbjerg. Based on [[Daniel Kahneman|Daniel Kahneman's]] work on the [[planning fallacy]] and optimism bias, Flyvbjerg pioneered [[reference class forecasting]] as a practical method for de-biasing megaproject plans. In his book, [[Thinking, Fast and Slow|''Thinking, Fast and Slow'']], Kahneman calls Flyvbjerg's insights on the planning fallacy and reference class forecasting, \"the single most important piece of advice regarding how to increase accuracy in forecasting.\"<ref>Kahneman, Daniel, 2011, ''Thinking, Fast and Slow'' (New York: Farrar, Straus and Giroux), p. 251.</ref> Daniel Kahneman is a key intellectual influence for Flyvbjerg's work on megaprojects, as is [[Nassim Nicholas Taleb]], especially his work on [[Black swan statistics|black swans]], and [[Martin Wachs]], who was Flyvbjerg's doctoral supervisor at UCLA. Flyvbjerg's key works on megaproject planning and management are the books ''[[Megaprojects and Risk|Megaprojects and Risk: An Anatomy of Ambition]]'' (with Nils Bruzelius and Werner Rothengatter),<ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, Nils Bruzelius, and Werner Rothengatter, 2003, ''Megaprojects and Risk: An Anatomy of Ambition'' (Cambridge University Press). </ref> ''[[The Oxford Handbook of Megaproject Management]]'',<ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, 2017, ed., ''The Oxford Handbook of Megaproject Management'' (Oxford: Oxford University Press).</ref> ''[[Decision-Making On Mega-Projects: Cost\u2013benefit Analysis, Planning, and Innovation]]'' (with Hugo Priemus and Bert van Wee),<ref>Priemus, Hugo, Bent Flyvbjerg, and Bert van Wee, 2008, eds., ''Decision-Making On Mega-Projects: Cost\u2013benefit Analysis, Planning, and Innovation'' (Cheltenham, UK and Northampton, MA, USA: Edward Elgar).</ref> and ''Megaproject Planning and Management: Essential Readings'',<ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, 2014, ed., ''Megaproject Planning and Management: Essential Readings'', vols. I-II (Cheltenham, UK and Northampton, MA: Edward Elgar).</ref> plus a number of research papers.<ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, 2016, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2767128 The Fallacy of Beneficial Ignorance: A Test of Hirschman's Hiding Hand],\" ''World Development'', vol. 84, May, pp. 176\u2013189. http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.worlddev.2016.03.012.</ref> <ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, 2014, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2424835 What You Should Know about Megaprojects and Why: An Overview],\" ''Project Management Journal'', vol. 45, no. 2, April-May, pp. 6-19. </ref> <ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, 2013, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2229700 Quality Control and Due Diligence in Project Management: Getting Decisions Right by Taking the Outside View],\" ''International Journal of Project Management'', vol. 31, no. 5, May, pp. 760\u2013774. DOI: 10.1016/j.ijproman.2012.10.007</ref> <ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, 2013, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2278887 How Planners Deal with Uncomfortable Knowledge: The Dubious Ethics of the American Planning Association],\" ''Cities'', vol. 32, June, pp. 157\u2013163.</ref><ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, 2006, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2238013 From Nobel Prize to Project Management: Getting Risks Right],\" ''Project Management Journal'', vol. 37, no. 3, August, pp. 5-15.</ref> <ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, and J. Rodney Turner, 2018, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=3012134 Do Classics Exist in Megaproject Management]?\", ''International Journal of Project Management'', vol. 36, no. 2, pp. 334-341, DOI: 10.1016/j.ijproman.2017.07.006. </ref> <ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, Allison Stewart, and Alexander Budzier, 2016, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2804554 The Oxford Olympics Study 2016: Cost and Cost Overrun at the Games],\" ''Sa\u00efd Business School Working Papers'' (Oxford: University of Oxford), July.</ref> <ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent and Alexander Budzier, 2011, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2229735 Why Your IT Project May Be Riskier than You Think],\" ''Harvard Business Review'', September, pp. 601-603.</ref> <ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, Massimo Garbuio''',''' and Dan Lovallo, 2009, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2229781 Delusion and Deception in Large Infrastructure Projects: Two Models for Explaining and Preventing Executive Disaster],\" ''California Management Review'', vol. 51, no. 2, Winter, pp. 170-193.</ref> <ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, Mette K. Skamris Holm, and S\u00f8ren L. Buhl, 2005, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2238050 How (In)accurate Are Demand Forecasts in Public Works Projects? The Case of Transportation].\" ''Journal of the American Planning Association'', vol. 71, no. 2, Spring, pp. 131-146. </ref> <ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, Mette K. Skamris Holm, and S\u00f8ren L. Buhl, 2002, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2278415 Underestimating Costs in Public Works Projects: Error or Lie]?\" ''Journal of the American Planning Association'', vol. 68, no. 3, Summer, pp. 279-295.</ref> <ref>Atif Ansar, Bent Flyvbjerg, Alexander Budzier, and Daniel Lunn, 2016, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2834326 Does Infrastructure Investment Lead to Economic Growth or Economic Fragility? Evidence from China],\" ''Oxford Review of Economic Policy'', vol. 32, no. 3, autumn, pp. 360\u2013390; DOI: 10.1093/oxrep/grw022</ref> <ref>Ansar, Atif, Bent Flyvbjerg, Alexander Budzier, and Daniel Lunn, 2014, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2406852 Should We Build More Large Dams? The Actual Costs of Hydropower Megaproject Development],\" ''Energy Policy'', vol. 69, March, pp. 43-56.</ref> Flyvbjerg has argued that his work on megaprojects constitutes an example of phronetic social science (see above).<ref>Flyvbjerg, Bent, 2012, \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2278219 Why Mass Media Matter and How to Work with Them: Phronesis and Megaprojects],\" in Bent Flyvbjerg, Todd Landman, and Sanford Schram, eds., ''Real Social Science: Applied Phronesis'' (Cambridge University Press), pp. 95-121.</ref>\n\n== Oxford BT Professorship in Major Programme Management ==\nIn 2007, [[BT Group]] (formerly British Telecom) donated funds to [[University of Oxford|the University of Oxford]] to set up permanently the [[List of professorships at the University of Oxford|BT Professorship and Chair in Major Programme Management]]. In 2008, Oxford University headhunted Bent Flyvbjerg for the position from Aalborg and Delft. Flyvbjerg is Oxford University's first BT Professor and inaugural Chair of Major Programme Management.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbs.ox.ac.uk/about-us/people/bent-flyvbjerg|title=Bent Flyvbjerg's Oxford University website|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Readership ==\nBent Flyvbjerg's publications are widely read and cited. [[Making Social Science Matter: Why Social Inquiry Fails and How It Can Succeed Again|His book ''Making Social Social Science Matter'': ''Why Social Inquiry Fails and How It Can Succeed Again'']] has more than 7,000 citations at [https://scholar.google.com/citations?hl=en&user=79htA7gAAAAJ&pagesize=100&view_op=list_works#d=gs_md_cita-d&u=%2Fcitations%3Fview_op%3Dview_citation%26hl%3Den%26user%3D79htA7gAAAAJ%26pagesize%3D100%26citation_for_view%3D79htA7gAAAAJ%3Au5HHmVD_uO8C%26tzom%3D0 Google Scholar], making it the most cited current book in the philosophy and methodology of social science. ''[[Megaprojects and Risk: An Anatomy of Ambition|Megaprojects and Risk. An Anatomy of Ambition]]'' has more than [https://scholar.google.com/citations?hl=en&user=79htA7gAAAAJ&pagesize=100&view_op=list_works#d=gs_md_cita-d&u=%2Fcitations%3Fview_op%3Dview_citation%26hl%3Den%26user%3D79htA7gAAAAJ%26pagesize%3D100%26citation_for_view%3D79htA7gAAAAJ%3A9yKSN-GCB0IC%26tzom%3D0 3,500 citations], making it the most cited book on megaproject planning and management. ''[[Rationality and Power: Democracy in Practice]]'' has more than [https://scholar.google.com/citations?hl=en&user=79htA7gAAAAJ&pagesize=100&view_op=list_works#d=gs_md_cita-d&u=%2Fcitations%3Fview_op%3Dview_citation%26hl%3Den%26user%3D79htA7gAAAAJ%26pagesize%3D100%26citation_for_view%3D79htA7gAAAAJ%3Ad1gkVwhDpl0C%26tzom%3D0 2,900 citations], making it one of the most cited books in city planning and management and winning Flyvbjerg the nomination of \"[https://www.amazon.com/Key-Thinkers-Cities-Regan-Koch/dp/1473907756/ref=sr_1_1?crid=1V2Y6G2U9Y2C1&keywords=key+thinkers+on+cities&qid=1581598403&sprefix=key+thinkers+on+cities%2Caps%2C237&sr=8-1 Key Thinker on Cities].\" Flyvbjerg's classic paper, \"Five Misunderstandings about Case-Study Research,\" has more than [https://scholar.google.com/citations?hl=en&user=79htA7gAAAAJ&pagesize=100&view_op=list_works#d=gs_md_cita-d&u=%2Fcitations%3Fview_op%3Dview_citation%26hl%3Den%26user%3D79htA7gAAAAJ%26pagesize%3D100%26citation_for_view%3D79htA7gAAAAJ%3Au-x6o8ySG0sC%26tzom%3D0 14,000 citations] at Google Scholar.\n\n== Honors and Awards ==\n\n* [https://www.pmi.org/about/awards/research-academic/research-achievement Project Management Institute Research Achievement Award], which \"recognizes and honors an individual whose work has significantly advanced the concepts, knowledge, and practices of project management through a published body of academic research,\" 2019.\n* [https://www.eiasm.net/about_eiasm/interdisciplinary-leader-award EIASM Interdisciplinary Leader Award], conferred by the Board of The European Institute for Advanced Studies in Management for \"exemplary contributions in interdisciplinary research,\" 2017.\n* [https://www.emeraldgrouppublishing.com/about/news/story.htm?id=3548 Emerald Citation of Excellence Award], in recognition of the paper \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2424835 What You Should Know about Megaprojects and Why: An Overview],\" ''Project Management Journal'', vol. 45, \"as one of the most highly cited and highly influential papers,\" 2017.\n* [https://www.pmi.org/about/awards/research-academic/pm-journal-paper-of-the-year Paper of the Year Award], conferred by the Project Management Institute and Project Management Journal for the paper \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2424835 What You Should Know about Megaprojects and Why: An Overview],\" ''Project Management Journal'', vol. 45, 2015.\n* [https://www.apm.org.uk/about-us/how-apm-is-run/honorary-fellows/ Honorary Fellow of the Association for Project Management], awarded for \"outstanding contributions to project management,\" 2011.\n* [http://www.aesop-planning.eu/en_GB/awards Association of European Schools of Planning's Best Published Paper Prize], awarded for the paper \"[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2230414 Policy and Planning for Large Infrastructure Projects: Problems, Causes, Cures],\" ''Environment and Planning B'', vol. 34, 2008.\n* [https://www.cies.org Fulbright Scholar], twice, awarded by the Fulbright Commission, Washington, DC.\n* [http://www.amscan.org Honorary Fellow under the American-Scandinavian Foundation].\n* [http://kongehuset.dk/en/the-monarchy-in-denmark/the-royal-symbols/the-royal-orders-of-chivalry Knighthood of the Order of the Dannebrog], awarded by Queen Margrethe II of Denmark for professional accomplishments, 2002.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.linkedin.com/in/flyvbjerg/|title=Full list of honors and awards for Bent Flyvbjerg.|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Advisory Work ==\nBent Flyvbjerg is co-founder and Chairman of [https://www.oxfordglobalprojects.com Oxford Global Projects]. He has advised government and business, including the US, UK, and Chinese governments and Fortune 500 companies. He also serves as external advisor to McKinsey & Co.\n\n==Books==\n*1998 ''[[Rationality and Power: Democracy in Practice]]'', University of Chicago Press ({{ISBN|0226254518}})\n*2001 ''[[Making Social Science Matter: Why Social Inquiry Fails and How It Can Succeed Again]]'', Cambridge University Press ({{ISBN|0-521-77568-X}})\n*2003 ''[[Megaprojects and Risk: An Anatomy of Ambition]]''. Cambridge University Press ({{ISBN|0-521-00946-4}})\n*2008 ''[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=tenILJ-MowQC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Decision-Making+on+Mega-Projects:+Cost-Benefit+Analysis,+Planning+and+Innovation&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwilv7uoq8_nAhVSilwKHT_jBPAQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=Decision-Making%20on%20Mega-Projects%3A%20Cost-Benefit%20Analysis%2C%20Planning%20and%20Innovation&f=false Decision-Making on Mega-Projects: Cost-Benefit Analysis, Planning and Innovation]'', Elgar ({{ISBN|978-1-84542-737-5}})\n*2012 [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=3I2fBeHZpBcC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Real+Social+Science:+Applied+Phronesis,+Cambridge+University+Press&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwib_rfHq8_nAhVGQ8AKHS4wCNcQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=Real%20Social%20Science%3A%20Applied%20Phronesis%2C%20Cambridge%20University%20Press&f=false ''Real Social Science: Applied Phronesis'', Cambridge University Press] ({{ISBN|978-0-521-16820-5}})\n*2014 ''[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=zOQhvgAACAAJ&dq=editions%3AQg6umPDRoXwC&source=gbs_book_other_versions Megaproject Planning and Management: Essential Readings, Volumes I-II]'', Elgar ({{ISBN|978-1-78100-170-7}})\n*2017 ''[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=J_8lDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=The+Oxford+Handbook+of+Megaproject+Management&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjGoviQrM_nAhXBkFwKHe8HDL4Q6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=The%20Oxford%20Handbook%20of%20Megaproject%20Management&f=false The Oxford Handbook of Megaproject Management]'', Oxford University Press ({{ISBN|978-0-19873-224-2}})\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Flyvbjerg, Bent}}\n[[Category:Danish urban planners]]\n[[Category:Delft University of Technology faculty]]\n[[Category:Danish geographers]]\n[[Category:Statutory Professors of the University of Oxford]]\n[[Category:Dutch urban planners]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Philosophers of social science]]\n[[Category:Academics of Sa\u00efd Business School]]\n[[Category:People associated with Aalborg University]]\n[[Category:Fulbright Scholars]]\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n", "name_user": "Scholarxx", "label": "safe", "comment": "Inserted 5 missing urls", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bent_Flyvbjerg"}
{"title_page": "Columbia University Vagelos College of Physicians and Surgeons", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name        = Columbia University<br>Vagelos College of Physicians and Surgeons\n|logo        = Columbia University College of Physicians and Surgeons Logo.gif \n|established = 1767\n|type        = [[Private school|Private]] [[medical school]]\n|dean        = Lee Goldman\n|city        = [[Manhattan]]\n|state       = [[New York (state)|New York]]\n|country     = United States\n|coordinates = {{coord|40.841519|-73.941139|type:edu_globe:earth_region:US-NY|display=inline,title}}\n|students    = '''Totals:''' 1,520<br>606 M.D.<br>94 M.D./Ph.D.<br>776 Ph.D.\n|faculty     = 4,300\n|campus      = [[urban area|Urban]]\n|website     = [https://www.ps.columbia.edu ps.columbia.edu]\n|endowment   = $1.136 billion<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ps.columbia.edu/about-us/facts-and-statistics|title=Facts & Statistics (2010) &#124; College of Physicians and Surgeons|publisher=Ps.columbia.edu|accessdate=October 24, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Columbia University Vagelos College of Physicians and Surgeons''' ('''VP&S''') is the graduate [[medical school]] of [[Columbia University]], located at the [[Columbia University Irving Medical Center]] in the [[Washington Heights, Manhattan|Washington Heights]] neighborhood of [[Manhattan]] with its affiliate [[NewYork\u2013Presbyterian Hospital]]. Founded in 1767 by [[Samuel Bard (physician)|Samuel Bard]] as the medical department of King's College (now [[Columbia University]]), VP&S was the first [[medical school]] in the [[Thirteen Colonies]] to award the [[Doctor of Medicine]] (MD) degree. Beginning in 1993, VP&S was also the first U.S. medical school to hold a [[white coat ceremony]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ps.columbia.edu/education/academic-programs/md-program/md-student-resources/office-student-affairs/white-coat|title=White Coat Ceremony '10 &#124; Columbia University Medical Center|publisher=Cumc.columbia.edu|date=September 13, 2010|accessdate=October 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAccording to ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'', VP&S is one of the most selective medical schools in the United States based on average [[Medical College Admission Test|MCAT]] score, [[Grade point average|GPA]], and acceptance rate.<ref>https://www.ps.columbia.edu/about-us/facts-and-statistics</ref> In 2018, 7,537 people applied and 1,007 were interviewed for 140 seats in its entering MD class.<ref>url=https://www.ps.columbia.edu/about-us/facts-and-statistics</ref> The median undergraduate GPA and average MCAT score for successful applicants in 2014 were 3.82 and 36, respectively. Columbia is ranked sixth for research among American medical schools by ''U.S. News & World Report''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Columbia University - Best Medical School|url=https://www.usnews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-medical-schools/columbia-university-04070|publisher=U.S. News & World Report}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Columbia became the first medical school in the nation to replace loans with scholarships for all students who qualify for financial aid. The scholarships are funded by an endowment that was established by Dr. [[P. Roy Vagelos]] and his wife Diana Vagelos; in December 2017, the 250-year-old medical school was renamed in their honor. The Vageloses committed more than $310 million to Columbia, $150 million of which was directed toward the scholarship fund.<ref>https://www.cuimc.columbia.edu/news/columbia-launches-scholarship-program-eliminate-medical-school-loans-students-financial-need</ref>\n\nColumbia is affiliated with [[NewYork-Presbyterian Hospital]], the nation's 5th-ranked hospital according to ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]''.<ref>[https://health.usnews.com/best-hospitals/area/ny/new-york-presbyterian-university-hospital-of-columbia-and-cornell-6210024 \"New York-Presbyterian Hospital-Columbia and Cornell\"] ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' (September 2, 2019)</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=2019-20 Best Hospitals Honor Roll and Medical Specialties Rankings|url=https://health.usnews.com/health-care/best-hospitals/articles/best-hospitals-honor-roll-and-overview|publisher=[[U.S. News & World Report]]|accessdate=October 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Curriculum==\nBeginning in the fall of 2009, the medical school implemented a new curriculum that differed markedly from more traditional structures. The largest change involved a reduction in the number of preclinical months from twenty-four to eighteen and the expansion of the electives and selectives period to fourteen months. Each student now is required to spend four to ten months working on a scholarly project before graduation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ps.columbia.edu/education/academic-programs/md-program/curriculum/md-curriculum/differentiation-and-integration-d-7|title=The Columbia Curriculum}}</ref>\n\n==Student life==\n[[File:ColumbiaMedicalCenter.jpeg|thumb|400px|Aerial view of the Columbia University Medical Center]]\n\n===Campus===\nSituated on land overlooking the [[Hudson River]] and separated from Columbia's undergraduate campus in [[Morningside Heights]] by approximately fifty blocks and the neighborhood of [[Harlem]], the [[Columbia University Medical Center]] has its own unique standing and identity. The campus comprises not only VP&S, but also the College of Dental Medicine (formerly the School of Dental and Oral Surgery), the School of Nursing, the Mailman School of Public Health, the Presbyterian portion of [[NewYork-Presbyterian Hospital]] (including the [[Morgan Stanley Children's Hospital]]) and the [[New York State Psychiatric Institute]]. Affiliated hospitals include [[Harlem Hospital Center|Harlem Hospital]], [[Stamford Hospital]] in [[Stamford, Connecticut|Stamford]], Connecticut, and [[Mary Imogene Bassett Hospital]] in [[Cooperstown, New York]]. In August 2016 the [https://www.cumc.columbia.edu/facilities-management/capital-projects/our-projects/roy-and-diana-vagelos-education-center Roy and Diana Vagelos Education Center], new 100,000-square-foot, 14-story glass medical education tower opened at 104 Haven Avenue, between 171st and 172nd Streets, near the northern tip of the campus. Housing options on Columbia's Medical Campus include Bard Hall and the Bard-Haven Towers, a complex of three, 31-story apartment buildings overlooking the [[Hudson River]] and the [[George Washington Bridge]]. Students are guaranteed housing on campus all years, although many students choose to live in other parts of New York City.\n\n===P&S Club===\nThere are student clubs covering a range of professional and personal interests, all of which fall under the umbrella of the P&S Club. One unusual element is the Bard Hall Players, a theatrical group entirely run by the students of the medical campus, and one of the largest and most active medical school theater groups in the country. They perform a musical and two plays each year. Founded over a century ago by [[John Mott]], the 1946 [[Nobel Peace Prize]] recipient, the P&S Club serves to support and provide activities and organizations for the enrichment of the lives of VP&S students. The P&S Club is well known for its humanitarian aims; most notably the 1917 purchase of a steam launch delivered to Sir William Grenfell, a physician living in [[Labrador]]. This launch was used to deliver medical services to the [[Inuit]] and [[First Nations]] fishermen living on the islands of the Labrador coast and frequently, was manned by P&S students.{{cn|date=December 2017}}\n\n==History==\n\n===Colonial years===\nIn 1767, Dr. [[Samuel Bard (physician)|Samuel Bard]], an alumnus of then-[[Columbia University|King's College]] and the [[University of Edinburgh Medical School]], opened a [[medical school]] at [[Columbia University|Columbia]]. At the time, the medical program at King's College was the first to open in the [[Province of New York]] and only the second to be opened in the [[Thirteen Colonies|American Colonies]]. The school was modelled on the [[University of Edinburgh Medical School]], which at the time was the world leader. Three years later, in 1770, King's College conferred its first [[Doctor of Medicine|medical degree]] to Robert Tucker, this would prove to be the first [[Doctor of Medicine]] (M.D.) awarded in the Thirteen Colonies. Prior to King's College of Medicine offering of the M.D. degree, other American and Canadian medical schools had been offering the [[Bachelor of Medicine and Surgery|M.B.]] degree. King's College continued to educate young doctors until 1776 when the school was forced to close due to the onset of the [[American Revolutionary War|Revolutionary War]] and the [[New York Campaign|occupation of New York]] by British soldiers. King's College remained closed until 1784 when the school was reopened as Columbia College and in December of that year, the faculty of the medical school were re-instated. In 1791, Bard, now a prominent colonial physician whom [[George Washington]] credited with saving his life, was named dean of the medical school.\n\n[[File:Columbia University College of Physicians and Surgeons entrance.jpg|thumb|right|250px|The original entrance to the College]]\n[[File:Bard Hall Columbia jeh.jpg|thumb|250px|upright|Bard Hall]]\n\n===Merger with the College of Physicians and Surgeons===\nIn 1807, with a growing young nation in need of adequately trained physicians, the [[New York State Board of Regents]] founded, under separate charter, the College of Physicians and Surgeons. Merely four years later, in 1811, Dr. Samuel Bard, dean of Columbia University Medical School, became president of the College. The year 1814 then saw the merger of Columbia University Medical School into the College of Physicians and Surgeons, a move that was made in an attempt to reverse what then was perceived as a period of decline for the medical school. \n[[File:(King1893NYC) pg280 COLLEGE OF PHYSICIANS AND SURGEONS, 437 WEST 59TH STREET.jpg|left|thumb|437 West 59th Street in 1893]]\nDespite this merger, the College of Physicians and Surgeons retained its independence from Columbia and it was only in 1860 that the College of Physicians and Surgeons, at that time occupying buildings across West Fifty-ninth Street from the [[Mount Sinai West|Roosevelt Hospital]] (its major teaching hospital at the time), after severing its ties to the New York Board of Regents and through agreement between the trustees of the College of Physicians and Surgeons and Columbia, became the official medical school of Columbia University. This new relationship between the college and Columbia was minimal at best, however, with the college retaining independence from Columbia. It was not until 1891 that the College of Physicians and Surgeons would be fully integrated and incorporated into Columbia. In 1886, the Sloane Maternity Hospital, later the [[Sloane Hospital for Women]], was founded as part of Physicians and Surgeons.\n\n===Medical Center Formation===\nIn 1911, Columbia University entered into a \"Formal Agreement of Alliance\" with Presbyterian Hospital, a hospital founded in 1868 by [[James Lenox]] a New York [[Philanthropy|philanthropist]]. It was this alliance, initiated by philanthropist [[Edward Harkness]], that helped to pave the way for the creation of a new medical center format. In 1928, the Columbia-Presbyterian Medical Center opened its doors in building largely funded by Harkness. Set on land in the [[Washington Heights, Manhattan|Washington Heights]] section of Manhattan, Columbia-Presbyterian Medical Center was the first place in the world to provide facilities for patient care, medical education, and research all under one roof. It was the first academic [[Academic health science centre|medical center]] and pioneered the practice of combining medical training with patient care. Included in this project with Presbyterian Hospital were the Babies Hospital, the Neurologic Institute of New York, and the New York State Psychiatric Institute; these were then joined in 1950 by the [[New York Orthopaedic Hospital]].\n\nIn 1997, the Presbyterian Hospital merged with New York Hospital (partner of [[Weill Cornell Medicine]] of [[Cornell University]]) to form the [[NewYork\u2013Presbyterian Hospital]]. This new hospital system also has incorporated many of the satellite hospitals and affiliated programs of these two institutions. While the two medical schools remain independent of one another, there has been significant cross-fertilization between the two campuses, leading to increasing numbers of shared research experiences and training programs. NYPH is now the largest private employer in New York City. All hospitals in the [[NewYork-Presbyterian Healthcare System]] are affiliated with either the Cornell or Columbia medical schools.\n\n===Renaming===\nAt the 2017 Crown Awards, President [[Lee Bollinger]] announced that the school would officially be renamed as the Columbia University Roy and Diana Vagelos College of Physicians and Surgeons. This decision was made in response to a gift of $250 million from Dr. P. Roy and Diana [[P. Roy Vagelos|Vagelos]].<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|title=With $250 Million Gift, Columbia Medical School Looks to End Student Debt|author=Otterman, Sharon|date=December 4, 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|issn=0362-4331|p=A21}}</ref> $150 million of the gift, was dedicated to endow a fund to help Columbia eliminate student loans for medical students who qualify for financial aid.<ref name=\":0\"/> The remaining $100 million will be divided equally to support precision medicine programs and basic science research as well as an endowed professorship in the Department of Medicine in honor of the Vagelos family's longtime doctor and friend, Thomas P. Jacobs, MD.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.legacy.com/obituaries/nytimes/obituary.aspx?n=thomas-jacobs&pid=192617902|title=Thomas Jacobs obituary|work=The New York Times|date=April 20, 2019|accessdate=October 24, 2019|via=[[Legacy.com]]}}</ref>\n\n==Prominent faculty==\nProminent faculty members include Nobel Prize laureates [[Richard Axel]], [[Eric Kandel]], and [[Joachim Frank]]; cardiothoracic surgeon, author, talk show host, and commentator [[Mehmet Oz]]; author [[Oliver Sacks]]; 2011 Pulitzer Prize winner for nonfiction [[Siddhartha Mukherjee]]; and [[Rudolph Leibel]] whose co-discovery of the [[hormone]] [[leptin]], and cloning of the [[leptin]] and [[leptin receptor]] genes, has had a major role in the area of understanding [[human]] [[obesity]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Shell E|title=The Hungry Gene: The Inside Story of the Obesity Industry|publisher=Atlantic Monthly Press|date=January 1, 2002|chapter=Chapter 4: On the Cutting Edge|isbn=978-1422352434}}</ref><ref>{{ cite book|author=Shell E|title=The Hungry Gene: The Inside Story of the Obesity Industry|publisher=Atlantic Monthly Press|date=January 1, 2002|chapter=Chapter 5: Hunger|isbn=978-1422352434}}</ref> [[Jean Emond|Jean C. Emond]], Thomas S. Zimmer Professor of Surgery, participated in the first living-donor [[liver transplantation]] in children in North America<ref>CUMC LiverMD 2007.</ref> and established the liver transplant program at Columbia, which has become one of the largest in the United States.<ref>CUMC Immunology 2007.</ref> In November 2018, [[Expertscape]] recognized Columbia as #1 in the world for expertise in [[Celiac Disease]] and Dr. Peter Green as the world's #1 expert.<ref name=\"rank_celiac_disease\">{{cite web|url=http://www.expertscape.com/the-leaders/celiac+disease|title=Expertscape: Celiac Disease, November 2018 |publisher=expertscape.com|date=November 2018|accessdate=October 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{Main category|Columbia University College of Physicians and Surgeons alumni}}\n\n===Medical innovators===\n*[[Virginia Apgar]] ([[Apgar score]])\n*[[Oswald Avery]] (pioneer in [[immunochemistry]])\n*[[Theodric Romeyn Beck|T. Romeyn Beck]] (pioneer in [[medical jurisprudence]]; authored first significant American book on [[forensic medicine]])\n*[[H. I. Biegeleisen]] (pioneer of [[phlebology]]; one of the first doctors in United States to use injection as a method of treating [[varicose veins]]; coined the term ''[[sclerotherapy]])\n*[[T. Berry Brazelton]] ([[Pediatrics|pediatrician]], Brazelton [[Neonatal Behavioral Assessment Scale]])\n*[[Charles R. Drew|Charles Drew]] (ground-breaking work in [[blood transfusions]], blood storage, large-scale [[blood banks]])\n*[[Tom Frieden]] (Director of [[U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC); New York City Health Commissioner)\n*[[Oliver Wolcott Gibbs]] (chemist; known for performing first [[Electrogravimetry|electrogravimetric analyses]]; [[National Academy of Sciences]], President (also a founding member), 1895\u20131900)\n*[[John Franklin Gray]] (pioneer in field of and first practitioner of homoeopathy in United States; also recognized as important medical reformer)\n*[[Peter K. Gregersen]] ([[Crafoord Prize]] in [[Polyarthritis]] in 2013)<ref>[http://www.crafoordprize.se/press/arkivpressreleases/thecrafoordprizeinpolyarthritis2013.5.74cf9d0413b817d9359dcd.htm The Crafoord Prize in Polyarthritis 2013], Crafoord Prize. Press Release. January 17, 2013. Retrieved October 24, 2019.</ref>\n*[[William Stewart Halsted|William Halsted]] (introduced several new operations, one of \"Big Four\" founding professors at [[Johns Hopkins Hospital]])\n*[[Jean Emily Henley]] (wrote the first widely used anesthesia textbook)\n*[[Robert Lefkowitz]] (U.S. [[National Medal of Science]], [[Shaw Prize]], 2012 [[Nobel Prize in Chemistry]])\n*[[Sean E. McCance]] ([[orthopedic surgeon]])\n*[[Walsh McDermott]] (infectious diseases and public health; pioneered the use of [[isoniazid]] to treat [[tuberculosis]])\n*[[David McDowell]] (psychiatrist, author, consultant)\n*[[Jean Baker Miller]] (psychoanalyst, feminist, social activist, wrote ''Toward a New Psychology of Women (1976))\n*[[Frederick F. Russell]] ([[Brigadier general (United States)|Brigadier General]]; U.S. Army physician who developed the first successful typhoid vaccine in 1909; [[Public Welfare Medal]])\n*[[Benjamin Spock]] (pediatrician, wrote ''[[The Common Sense Book of Baby and Child Care]]'')\n*[[Albert Starr]] (2007 [[Lasker Award]]; [[cardiovascular surgeon]]; pioneer, [[inventor]], Starr [[heart valve]])\n*[[Paul Stelzer]] ([[cardiothoracic surgeon]])\n*[[P. Roy Vagelos]] (president, CEO, chairman of pharmaceutical company [[Merck & Co.|Merck]])\n*[[Allen Whipple]] ([[Whipple procedure]], [[Whipple's triad]])\n\n===Nobel laureates===\n*[[Baruch Samuel Blumberg]]\n*[[Joshua Lederberg]]\n*[[Robert J. Lefkowitz]] (best known for his work with [[G protein-coupled receptor]]s for which he won the 2012 [[Nobel Prize]] in Chemistry)\n*[[Dickinson W. Richards]]\n*[[Harold Varmus]] (Director, [[National Institutes of Health]]; Director, [[National Cancer Institute]]; President, [[Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center]])\n\n===Writers===\n*[[Jacob M. Appel|Jacob Appel]] (2004 [[William Faulkner \u2013 William Wisdom Creative Writing Competition]])\n*[[Robert Coles (psychiatrist)|Robert Coles]] ([[Pulitzer Prize for General Non-Fiction]], [[MacArthur Award]] \"genius grant\", [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]], [[National Humanities Medal]])\n*[[Robin Cook (American novelist)|Robin Cook]] (100 million+ copies of works in print)\n*[[Jerome Groopman]]\n*[[Walker Percy]] ([[National Book Award for Fiction]], \"''Time'' 100 Best English-language Novels from 1923 to 2005\")\n*[[John E. Sarno]] (originator of the diagnosis of psychosomatic condition, [[tension myositis syndrome]])\n\n===Others===\nOther alumni include astronaut [[Story Musgrave]], Olympic champion [[Jenny Thompson]] (twelve medals, including eight gold medals), former Afghan prime minister [[Abdul Zahir (politician)|Abdul Zahir]], mayor of the City of [[Rancho Cucamonga, California]] (2006\u2013) [[Don Kurth]], and philanthropists [[Theodore K. Lawless]] and [[Jean Shafiroff]]. [[George Fletcher Chandler]] served with the [[United States Army Medical Corps|US Army Medical Corps]] and practiced as a physician and surgeon throughout New York in addition to organizing and serving as the first Superintendent of the [[New York State Police]].\n\n[[Serbs|Serb]] politician and accused [[war criminal]] [[Radovan Karad\u017ei\u0107]] studied at Columbia for a year. Former [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] player [[Mark Pope]] attended P&S, but left to coach college basketball.\n\n[[John L. Leal]]'s application of chlorine disinfection technology and his defense of the chemical's use, contributed significantly to the eradication of typhoid fever and other waterborne diseases in the U.S.\n\n==In fiction==\n{{See also|Columbia University in popular culture}}\n*The characters [[Derek Shepherd]], [[Mark Sloan (Grey's Anatomy)|Mark Sloan]], and [[Addison Montgomery]] from medical drama ''[[Grey's Anatomy]]'' and [[Sam Bennett (Private Practice)|Sam Bennett]] and [[Naomi Bennett]] from the spinoff series ''[[Private Practice (TV series)|Private Practice]]'' attended P&S together\n*Joel Fleischman ([[Rob Morrow]]) in ''[[Northern Exposure]]''\n*Dr. [[The Adventures of Buckaroo Banzai Across the 8th Dimension|Buckaroo Banzai]] ([[Peter Weller]]) and Dr. Sidney Zweibel ([[Jeff Goldblum]]) were P&S classmates in ''[[The Adventures of Buckaroo Banzai Across the 8th Dimension]]'' (1984)\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Columbia University College of Physicians and Surgeons}}\n*{{official website|http://ps.columbia.edu/}}\n\n{{Columbia}}\n{{NewYork\u2013Presbyterian Healthcare System}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Columbia University College Of Physicians And Surgeons}}\n[[Category:Columbia University]]\n[[Category:NewYork\u2013Presbyterian Healthcare System]]\n[[Category:Schools of medicine in New York City]]\n[[Category:Washington Heights, Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in the 1760s]]\n[[Category:1767 establishments in New York]]\n[[Category:Ivy League medical schools]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name        = Columbia University<br>Vagelos College of Physicians and Surgeons\n|logo        = Columbia University College of Physicians and Surgeons Logo.gif \n|established = 1767\n|type        = [[Private school|Private]] [[medical school]]\n|dean        = Lee Goldman\n|city        = [[Manhattan]]\n|state       = [[New York (state)|New York]]\n|country     = United States\n|coordinates = {{coord|40.841519|-73.941139|type:edu_globe:earth_region:US-NY|display=inline,title}}\n|students    = '''Totals:''' 1,520<br>606 M.D.<br>94 M.D./Ph.D.<br>776 Ph.D.\n|faculty     = 4,300\n|campus      = [[urban area|Urban]]\n|website     = [https://www.ps.columbia.edu ps.columbia.edu]\n|endowment   = $1.136 billion<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ps.columbia.edu/about-us/facts-and-statistics|title=Facts & Statistics (2010) &#124; College of Physicians and Surgeons|publisher=Ps.columbia.edu|accessdate=October 24, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Columbia University Vagelos College of Physicians and Surgeons''' ('''VP&S''') is the graduate [[medical school]] of [[Columbia University]], located at the [[Columbia University Irving Medical Center]] in the [[Washington Heights, Manhattan|Washington Heights]] neighborhood of [[Manhattan]] with its affiliate [[NewYork\u2013Presbyterian Hospital]]. Founded in 1767 by [[Samuel Bard (physician)|Samuel Bard]] as the medical department of King's College (now [[Columbia University]]), VP&S was the first [[medical school]] in the [[Thirteen Colonies]] to award the [[Doctor of Medicine]] (MD) degree. Beginning in 1993, VP&S was also the first U.S. medical school to hold a [[white coat ceremony]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ps.columbia.edu/education/academic-programs/md-program/md-student-resources/office-student-affairs/white-coat|title=White Coat Ceremony '10 &#124; Columbia University Medical Center|publisher=Cumc.columbia.edu|date=September 13, 2010|accessdate=October 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAccording to ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'', VP&S is one of the most selective medical schools in the United States based on average [[Medical College Admission Test|MCAT]] score, [[Grade point average|GPA]], and acceptance rate.<ref>https://www.ps.columbia.edu/about-us/facts-and-statistics</ref> In 2018, 7,537 people applied and 1,007 were interviewed for 140 seats in its entering MD class.<ref>url=https://www.ps.columbia.edu/about-us/facts-and-statistics</ref> The median undergraduate GPA and average MCAT score for successful applicants in 2014 were 3.82 and 36, respectively. Columbia is ranked sixth for research among American medical schools by ''U.S. News & World Report''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Columbia University - Best Medical School|url=https://www.usnews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-medical-schools/columbia-university-04070|publisher=U.S. News & World Report}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Columbia became the first medical school in the nation to replace loans with scholarships for all students who qualify for financial aid. The scholarships are funded by an endowment that was established by Dr. [[P. Roy Vagelos]] and his wife Diana Vagelos; in December 2017, the 250-year-old medical school was renamed in their honor. The Vageloses committed more than $310 million to Columbia, $150 million of which was directed toward the scholarship fund.<ref>https://www.cuimc.columbia.edu/news/columbia-launches-scholarship-program-eliminate-medical-school-loans-students-financial-need</ref>\n\nColumbia is affiliated with [[NewYork-Presbyterian Hospital]], the nation's 5th-ranked hospital according to ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]''.<ref>[https://health.usnews.com/best-hospitals/area/ny/new-york-presbyterian-university-hospital-of-columbia-and-cornell-6210024 \"New York-Presbyterian Hospital-Columbia and Cornell\"] ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' (September 2, 2019)</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=2019-20 Best Hospitals Honor Roll and Medical Specialties Rankings|url=https://health.usnews.com/health-care/best-hospitals/articles/best-hospitals-honor-roll-and-overview|publisher=[[U.S. News & World Report]]|accessdate=October 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Curriculum==\nBeginning in the fall of 2009, the medical school implemented a new curriculum that differed markedly from more traditional structures. The largest change involved a reduction in the number of preclinical months from twenty-four to eighteen and the expansion of the electives and selectives period to fourteen months. Each student now is required to spend four to ten months working on a scholarly project before graduation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ps.columbia.edu/education/academic-programs/md-program/curriculum/md-curriculum/differentiation-and-integration-d-7|title=The Columbia Curriculum}}</ref>\n\n==Student life==\n[[File:ColumbiaMedicalCenter.jpeg|thumb|400px|Aerial view of the Columbia University Medical Center]]\n\n===Campus===\nSituated on land overlooking the [[Hudson River]] and separated from Columbia's undergraduate campus in [[Morningside Heights]] by approximately fifty blocks and the neighborhood of [[Harlem]], the [[Columbia University Medical Center]] has its own unique standing and identity. The campus comprises not only VP&S, but also the College of Dental Medicine (formerly the School of Dental and Oral Surgery), the School of Nursing, the Mailman School of Public Health, the Presbyterian portion of [[NewYork-Presbyterian Hospital]] (including the [[Morgan Stanley Children's Hospital]]) and the [[New York State Psychiatric Institute]]. Affiliated hospitals include [[Harlem Hospital Center|Harlem Hospital]], [[Stamford Hospital]] in [[Stamford, Connecticut|Stamford]], Connecticut, and [[Mary Imogene Bassett Hospital]] in [[Cooperstown, New York]]. In August 2016 the [https://www.cumc.columbia.edu/facilities-management/capital-projects/our-projects/roy-and-diana-vagelos-education-center Roy and Diana Vagelos Education Center], new 100,000-square-foot, 14-story glass medical education tower opened at 104 Haven Avenue, between 171st and 172nd Streets, near the northern tip of the campus. Housing options on Columbia's Medical Campus include Bard Hall and the Bard-Haven Towers, a complex of three, 31-story apartment buildings overlooking the [[Hudson River]] and the [[George Washington Bridge]]. Students are guaranteed housing on campus all years, although many students choose to live in other parts of New York City.\n\n===P&S Club===\nThere are student clubs covering a range of professional and personal interests, all of which fall under the umbrella of the P&S Club. One unusual element is the Bard Hall Players, a theatrical group entirely run by the students of the medical campus, and one of the largest and most active medical school theater groups in the country. They perform a musical and two plays each year. Founded over a century ago by [[John Mott]], the 1946 [[Nobel Peace Prize]] recipient, the P&S Club serves to support and provide activities and organizations for the enrichment of the lives of VP&S students. The P&S Club is well known for its humanitarian aims; most notably the 1917 purchase of a steam launch delivered to Sir William Grenfell, a physician living in [[Labrador]]. This launch was used to deliver medical services to the [[Inuit]] and [[First Nations]] fishermen living on the islands of the Labrador coast and frequently, was manned by P&S students.{{cn|date=December 2017}}\n\n==History==\n\n===Colonial years===\nIn 1767, Dr. [[Samuel Bard (physician)|Samuel Bard]], an alumnus of King's College (now [[Columbia University]]) and the [[University of Edinburgh Medical School]], opened a [[medical school]] at [[Columbia University|Columbia]]. At the time, the medical program at King's College was the first to open in the [[Province of New York]] and only the second to be opened in the [[Thirteen Colonies|American Colonies]]. The school was modelled on the [[University of Edinburgh Medical School]], which at the time was the world leader. Three years later, in 1770, King's College conferred its first [[Doctor of Medicine|medical degree]] to Robert Tucker, this would prove to be the first [[Doctor of Medicine]] (M.D.) awarded in the Thirteen Colonies. Prior to King's College of Medicine offering of the M.D. degree, other American and Canadian medical schools had been offering the [[Bachelor of Medicine and Surgery|M.B.]] degree. King's College continued to educate young doctors until 1776 when the school was forced to close due to the onset of the [[American Revolutionary War|Revolutionary War]] and the [[New York Campaign|occupation of New York]] by British soldiers. King's College remained closed until 1784 when the school was reopened as Columbia College and in December of that year, the faculty of the medical school were re-instated. In 1791, Bard, now a prominent colonial physician whom [[George Washington]] credited with saving his life, was named dean of the medical school.\n\n[[File:Columbia University College of Physicians and Surgeons entrance.jpg|thumb|right|250px|The original entrance to the College]]\n[[File:Bard Hall Columbia jeh.jpg|thumb|250px|upright|Bard Hall]]\n\n===Merger with the College of Physicians and Surgeons===\nIn 1807, with a growing young nation in need of adequately trained physicians, the [[New York State Board of Regents]] founded, under separate charter, the College of Physicians and Surgeons. Merely four years later, in 1811, Dr. Samuel Bard, dean of Columbia University Medical School, became president of the College. The year 1814 then saw the merger of Columbia University Medical School into the College of Physicians and Surgeons, a move that was made in an attempt to reverse what then was perceived as a period of decline for the medical school. \n[[File:(King1893NYC) pg280 COLLEGE OF PHYSICIANS AND SURGEONS, 437 WEST 59TH STREET.jpg|left|thumb|437 West 59th Street in 1893]]\nDespite this merger, the College of Physicians and Surgeons retained its independence from Columbia and it was only in 1860 that the College of Physicians and Surgeons, at that time occupying buildings across West Fifty-ninth Street from the [[Mount Sinai West|Roosevelt Hospital]] (its major teaching hospital at the time), after severing its ties to the New York Board of Regents and through agreement between the trustees of the College of Physicians and Surgeons and Columbia, became the official medical school of Columbia University. This new relationship between the college and Columbia was minimal at best, however, with the college retaining independence from Columbia. It was not until 1891 that the College of Physicians and Surgeons would be fully integrated and incorporated into Columbia. In 1886, the Sloane Maternity Hospital, later the [[Sloane Hospital for Women]], was founded as part of Physicians and Surgeons.\n\n===Medical Center Formation===\nIn 1911, Columbia University entered into a \"Formal Agreement of Alliance\" with Presbyterian Hospital, a hospital founded in 1868 by [[James Lenox]] a New York [[Philanthropy|philanthropist]]. It was this alliance, initiated by philanthropist [[Edward Harkness]], that helped to pave the way for the creation of a new medical center format. In 1928, the Columbia-Presbyterian Medical Center opened its doors in building largely funded by Harkness. Set on land in the [[Washington Heights, Manhattan|Washington Heights]] section of Manhattan, Columbia-Presbyterian Medical Center was the first place in the world to provide facilities for patient care, medical education, and research all under one roof. It was the first academic [[Academic health science centre|medical center]] and pioneered the practice of combining medical training with patient care. Included in this project with Presbyterian Hospital were the Babies Hospital, the Neurologic Institute of New York, and the New York State Psychiatric Institute; these were then joined in 1950 by the [[New York Orthopaedic Hospital]].\n\nIn 1997, the Presbyterian Hospital merged with New York Hospital (partner of [[Weill Cornell Medicine]] of [[Cornell University]]) to form the [[NewYork\u2013Presbyterian Hospital]]. This new hospital system also has incorporated many of the satellite hospitals and affiliated programs of these two institutions. While the two medical schools remain independent of one another, there has been significant cross-fertilization between the two campuses, leading to increasing numbers of shared research experiences and training programs. NYPH is now the largest private employer in New York City. All hospitals in the [[NewYork-Presbyterian Healthcare System]] are affiliated with either the Cornell or Columbia medical schools.\n\n===Renaming===\nAt the 2017 Crown Awards, President [[Lee Bollinger]] announced that the school would officially be renamed as the Columbia University Roy and Diana Vagelos College of Physicians and Surgeons. This decision was made in response to a gift of $250 million from Dr. P. Roy and Diana [[P. Roy Vagelos|Vagelos]].<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|title=With $250 Million Gift, Columbia Medical School Looks to End Student Debt|author=Otterman, Sharon|date=December 4, 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|issn=0362-4331|p=A21}}</ref> $150 million of the gift, was dedicated to endow a fund to help Columbia eliminate student loans for medical students who qualify for financial aid.<ref name=\":0\"/> The remaining $100 million will be divided equally to support precision medicine programs and basic science research as well as an endowed professorship in the Department of Medicine in honor of the Vagelos family's longtime doctor and friend, Thomas P. Jacobs, MD.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.legacy.com/obituaries/nytimes/obituary.aspx?n=thomas-jacobs&pid=192617902|title=Thomas Jacobs obituary|work=The New York Times|date=April 20, 2019|accessdate=October 24, 2019|via=[[Legacy.com]]}}</ref>\n\n==Prominent faculty==\nProminent faculty members include Nobel Prize laureates [[Richard Axel]], [[Eric Kandel]], and [[Joachim Frank]]; cardiothoracic surgeon, author, talk show host, and commentator [[Mehmet Oz]]; author [[Oliver Sacks]]; 2011 Pulitzer Prize winner for nonfiction [[Siddhartha Mukherjee]]; and [[Rudolph Leibel]] whose co-discovery of the [[hormone]] [[leptin]], and cloning of the [[leptin]] and [[leptin receptor]] genes, has had a major role in the area of understanding [[human]] [[obesity]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Shell E|title=The Hungry Gene: The Inside Story of the Obesity Industry|publisher=Atlantic Monthly Press|date=January 1, 2002|chapter=Chapter 4: On the Cutting Edge|isbn=978-1422352434}}</ref><ref>{{ cite book|author=Shell E|title=The Hungry Gene: The Inside Story of the Obesity Industry|publisher=Atlantic Monthly Press|date=January 1, 2002|chapter=Chapter 5: Hunger|isbn=978-1422352434}}</ref> [[Jean Emond|Jean C. Emond]], Thomas S. Zimmer Professor of Surgery, participated in the first living-donor [[liver transplantation]] in children in North America<ref>CUMC LiverMD 2007.</ref> and established the liver transplant program at Columbia, which has become one of the largest in the United States.<ref>CUMC Immunology 2007.</ref> In November 2018, [[Expertscape]] recognized Columbia as #1 in the world for expertise in [[Celiac Disease]] and Dr. Peter Green as the world's #1 expert.<ref name=\"rank_celiac_disease\">{{cite web|url=http://www.expertscape.com/the-leaders/celiac+disease|title=Expertscape: Celiac Disease, November 2018 |publisher=expertscape.com|date=November 2018|accessdate=October 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{Main category|Columbia University College of Physicians and Surgeons alumni}}\n\n===Medical innovators===\n*[[Virginia Apgar]] ([[Apgar score]])\n*[[Oswald Avery]] (pioneer in [[immunochemistry]])\n*[[Theodric Romeyn Beck|T. Romeyn Beck]] (pioneer in [[medical jurisprudence]]; authored first significant American book on [[forensic medicine]])\n*[[H. I. Biegeleisen]] (pioneer of [[phlebology]]; one of the first doctors in United States to use injection as a method of treating [[varicose veins]]; coined the term ''[[sclerotherapy]])\n*[[T. Berry Brazelton]] ([[Pediatrics|pediatrician]], Brazelton [[Neonatal Behavioral Assessment Scale]])\n*[[Charles R. Drew|Charles Drew]] (ground-breaking work in [[blood transfusions]], blood storage, large-scale [[blood banks]])\n*[[Tom Frieden]] (Director of [[U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC); New York City Health Commissioner)\n*[[Oliver Wolcott Gibbs]] (chemist; known for performing first [[Electrogravimetry|electrogravimetric analyses]]; [[National Academy of Sciences]], President (also a founding member), 1895\u20131900)\n*[[John Franklin Gray]] (pioneer in field of and first practitioner of homoeopathy in United States; also recognized as important medical reformer)\n*[[Peter K. Gregersen]] ([[Crafoord Prize]] in [[Polyarthritis]] in 2013)<ref>[http://www.crafoordprize.se/press/arkivpressreleases/thecrafoordprizeinpolyarthritis2013.5.74cf9d0413b817d9359dcd.htm The Crafoord Prize in Polyarthritis 2013], Crafoord Prize. Press Release. January 17, 2013. Retrieved October 24, 2019.</ref>\n*[[William Stewart Halsted|William Halsted]] (introduced several new operations, one of \"Big Four\" founding professors at [[Johns Hopkins Hospital]])\n*[[Jean Emily Henley]] (wrote the first widely used anesthesia textbook)\n*[[Robert Lefkowitz]] (U.S. [[National Medal of Science]], [[Shaw Prize]], 2012 [[Nobel Prize in Chemistry]])\n*[[Sean E. McCance]] ([[orthopedic surgeon]])\n*[[Walsh McDermott]] (infectious diseases and public health; pioneered the use of [[isoniazid]] to treat [[tuberculosis]])\n*[[David McDowell]] (psychiatrist, author, consultant)\n*[[Jean Baker Miller]] (psychoanalyst, feminist, social activist, wrote ''Toward a New Psychology of Women (1976))\n*[[Frederick F. Russell]] ([[Brigadier general (United States)|Brigadier General]]; U.S. Army physician who developed the first successful typhoid vaccine in 1909; [[Public Welfare Medal]])\n*[[Benjamin Spock]] (pediatrician, wrote ''[[The Common Sense Book of Baby and Child Care]]'')\n*[[Albert Starr]] (2007 [[Lasker Award]]; [[cardiovascular surgeon]]; pioneer, [[inventor]], Starr [[heart valve]])\n*[[Paul Stelzer]] ([[cardiothoracic surgeon]])\n*[[P. Roy Vagelos]] (president, CEO, chairman of pharmaceutical company [[Merck & Co.|Merck]])\n*[[Allen Whipple]] ([[Whipple procedure]], [[Whipple's triad]])\n\n===Nobel laureates===\n*[[Baruch Samuel Blumberg]]\n*[[Joshua Lederberg]]\n*[[Robert J. Lefkowitz]] (best known for his work with [[G protein-coupled receptor]]s for which he won the 2012 [[Nobel Prize]] in Chemistry)\n*[[Dickinson W. Richards]]\n*[[Harold Varmus]] (Director, [[National Institutes of Health]]; Director, [[National Cancer Institute]]; President, [[Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center]])\n\n===Writers===\n*[[Jacob M. Appel|Jacob Appel]] (2004 [[William Faulkner \u2013 William Wisdom Creative Writing Competition]])\n*[[Robert Coles (psychiatrist)|Robert Coles]] ([[Pulitzer Prize for General Non-Fiction]], [[MacArthur Award]] \"genius grant\", [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]], [[National Humanities Medal]])\n*[[Robin Cook (American novelist)|Robin Cook]] (100 million+ copies of works in print)\n*[[Jerome Groopman]]\n*[[Walker Percy]] ([[National Book Award for Fiction]], \"''Time'' 100 Best English-language Novels from 1923 to 2005\")\n*[[John E. Sarno]] (originator of the diagnosis of psychosomatic condition, [[tension myositis syndrome]])\n\n===Others===\nOther alumni include astronaut [[Story Musgrave]], Olympic champion [[Jenny Thompson]] (twelve medals, including eight gold medals), former Afghan prime minister [[Abdul Zahir (politician)|Abdul Zahir]], mayor of the City of [[Rancho Cucamonga, California]] (2006\u2013) [[Don Kurth]], and philanthropists [[Theodore K. Lawless]] and [[Jean Shafiroff]]. [[George Fletcher Chandler]] served with the [[United States Army Medical Corps|US Army Medical Corps]] and practiced as a physician and surgeon throughout New York in addition to organizing and serving as the first Superintendent of the [[New York State Police]].\n\n[[Serbs|Serb]] politician and accused [[war criminal]] [[Radovan Karad\u017ei\u0107]] studied at Columbia for a year. Former [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] player [[Mark Pope]] attended P&S, but left to coach college basketball.\n\n[[John L. Leal]]'s application of chlorine disinfection technology and his defense of the chemical's use, contributed significantly to the eradication of typhoid fever and other waterborne diseases in the U.S.\n\n==In fiction==\n{{See also|Columbia University in popular culture}}\n*The characters [[Derek Shepherd]], [[Mark Sloan (Grey's Anatomy)|Mark Sloan]], and [[Addison Montgomery]] from medical drama ''[[Grey's Anatomy]]'' and [[Sam Bennett (Private Practice)|Sam Bennett]] and [[Naomi Bennett]] from the spinoff series ''[[Private Practice (TV series)|Private Practice]]'' attended P&S together\n*Joel Fleischman ([[Rob Morrow]]) in ''[[Northern Exposure]]''\n*Dr. [[The Adventures of Buckaroo Banzai Across the 8th Dimension|Buckaroo Banzai]] ([[Peter Weller]]) and Dr. Sidney Zweibel ([[Jeff Goldblum]]) were P&S classmates in ''[[The Adventures of Buckaroo Banzai Across the 8th Dimension]]'' (1984)\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Columbia University College of Physicians and Surgeons}}\n*{{official website|http://ps.columbia.edu/}}\n\n{{Columbia}}\n{{NewYork\u2013Presbyterian Healthcare System}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Columbia University College Of Physicians And Surgeons}}\n[[Category:Columbia University]]\n[[Category:NewYork\u2013Presbyterian Healthcare System]]\n[[Category:Schools of medicine in New York City]]\n[[Category:Washington Heights, Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in the 1760s]]\n[[Category:1767 establishments in New York]]\n[[Category:Ivy League medical schools]]\n", "name_user": "Thehornet", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eColonial years", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Columbia_University_Vagelos_College_of_Physicians_and_Surgeons"}
{"title_page": "Sahaptin language", "text_new": "{{Infobox language\n|name=Sahaptin\n'''|states=[[United States]]'''\n|region=[[Washington (U.S. state)|Washington]], [[Oregon]], and [[Idaho]]\n|ethnicity={{sigfig|9,820|1}}<!--data supports 1 sig fig--> [[Sahaptin]]s (1977)<ref name=e18/>\n|speakers=100\u2013125\n|date=2007\n|ref=e18\n|familycolor=American\n|fam1=[[Plateau Penutian languages|Plateau Penutian]]\n|fam2=[[Sahaptian languages|Sahaptian]]\n|linglist=qot\n|lingname=Sahaptin\n|lc1=uma  |ld1=[[Umatilla language|Umatilla]] \n|lc2=waa  |ld2=[[Walla Walla tribe|Walla Walla]] \n|lc3=yak  |ld3=[[Yakama Nation|Yakama]] \n|lc4=tqn  |ld4=[[Warm Springs tribes|Tenino]] \n|glotto=saha1240\n|glottorefname=Sahaptin\n}}\n\n'''Sahaptin''' or '''Shahaptin''' is one of the two-language [[Sahaptian languages|Sahaptian]] branch of the [[Plateau Penutian languages|Plateau Penutian]] family spoken in a section of the northwestern plateau along the [[Columbia River]] and its tributaries in southern Washington, northern Oregon, and southwestern Idaho, in the [[United States]].;<ref>[[#refMithun1999|Mithun, 1999]]</ref> the other language is [[Nez Perce language|Nez Perce]] or ''Niimi'ipuut\u00edmt''. Many of the tribes that surrounded the land were skilled with horses and trading with one another; some tribes were known for their [[horse breeding]] which resulted in today's [[Appaloosa]] or [[Cayuse horse]].\n\nThe word ''Sahaptin/Shahaptin'' is not the one used by the tribes that speak it, but from the Columbia Salish name, '''S\u0127\u00e1pt\u0259n\u0259xw / S-h\u00e1ptinoxw''', which means \"stranger in the land\". This is the name the [[Wenatchi]] (in Sahaptin: Win\u00e1tshapam) and Kawaxchinl\u00e1ma (who speak Columbia Salish) traditionally call the [[Nez Perce people]]. Early white explorers mistakenly applied the name to all the various Sahaptin speaking people, as well as to the Nez Perce. Sahaptin is spoken by various tribes of the Washington Reservations; Yakama, Warm Springs, Umatilla; and also spoken in many smaller communities, including one in Oregon, Celilo.\n\nThe [[Yakama]] tribal cultural resources program has been promoting the use of the traditional name of the language, ''Ichishk\u00edin S\u0268\u0301nwit'' (\u2033this language\u2033), instead of the Salish term ''Sahaptin''.<ref>Beavert, Virginia and Hargus, Sharon ''Ichishk\u00edin s\u0268\u0301nwit yakama = Yakima Sahaptin dictionary''. Toppenish, Wash.: Heritage University, Seattle: in association with the University of Washington Press, 2009; 492 pp. OCLC 268797329.</ref>\n\n==Dialects==\nSahaptin has three mutually intelligible dialects in a [[dialect cluster]] :<ref>Sharon Hargus 2012, [http://faculty.washington.edu/sharon/1P_Clitics_NW_Sahaptin.pdf First position clitics in Northwest Sahaptin]</ref>\n*Northern Sahaptin group\n**Northwest Sahaptin dialect cluster: '''[[Klickitat people|Klickitat (Klikitat)]]''' (Yakama name: Xw\u00e1lxwaypam or L'ataxat), '''[[Cowlitz people|Tainapam]]''' (Taidnapam / T\u00e1ytnapam or Upper Cowlitz), Upper Nisqually (Meshal / Mashel or Mica'l, also known as Mishalpam), '''[[Yakama|Yakama (Yakima)]]''' (Lower or Yakama proper, autonym: M\u00e1machatpam), '''[[Kittitas people|Kittitas]]''' (Upper Yakama, autonym: Pshw\u00e1napam or Pshwanpawam)\n**Northeast Sahaptin dialect cluster: '''[[Wanapum|Wanapum (Wanapam)]]''' (W\u00e1napam), '''[[Palus people|Palouse (Palus)]]''' (Yakama name: Pel\u00fauspem), Lower Snake (Chamnapam, Wauyukma, and Naxiyampam), '''[[Walla Walla tribe|Walla Walla]]''' (Waluulapan)\n*Southern Sahaptin group (Columbia River cluster): '''[[Umatilla language|Umatilla]]''' (Rock Creek Indians, Yakama name: Amatalamlama; Imatalamlama), Skin-pah (Sk'in tribe or Sawpaw, also known as Fall Bridge and Rock Creek people or K'mill\u00e1ma, a Tenino subtribe; perhaps another Yakama name for the Umatilla, who were known as Rock Creek Indians), '''[[Tenino people|Tenino]]''' (Tygh Valley dialect of the [[Tygh people|Tygh]] (Taih, Tyigh or Tayx\u026b\u00e1ma) or \"Upper Deschutes\", Celilo dialect of the [[Wyam people|Wyam (Way\u00e1m\u026b\u00e1ma)]] (Yakama name: Way\u00e1mpam) or \"Lower Deschutes\", also known as \"Celilo Indians\", Tenino dialect of the [[Dalles Tenino people|Dalles Tenino]] or \"Tinainu (Tinaynu\u026b\u00e1ma)\"; John Day dialect oft the [[Dock-Spus people|Dock-Spus (Tukspush or Takspas\u026b\u00e1ma)]] or \"John Day.\")\n\n==Grammar==\nThere are published grammars,<ref>[[#refJacobs1931|Jacobs, 1931]].</ref><ref>[[#refRigsby and Rude1996|Rigsby and Rude, 1996]].</ref> a recent dictionary,<ref>[[#refBeavert & Hargus2009|Beavert & Hargus, 2009]].</ref> and a corpus of published texts.<ref>[[#refJacobs1929|Jacobs, 1929]].</ref><ref>[[#refJacobs1937|Jacobs, 1937]].</ref>  Sahaptin has a [[split ergativity|split ergative]] syntax, with direct-inverse voicing and several applicative constructions.<ref>[[#refRude2009|Rude, 2009]].</ref>\n\nThe [[ergative case]] inflects third-person nominals only when the direct object is first- or second-person (the examples below are from the Umatilla dialect):\n\n;1) i-q\u0313\u00ednu-\u0161ana y\u00e1ka  paan\u00e1y\n:3<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">nom</span>-see-<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">asp</span> bear 3<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">acc.sg</span>\n:\u2018the bear saw him\u2019\n\n;2) i-q\u0313\u00ednu-\u0161ana=a\u0161  y\u00e1ka-n\u0268m\n:3<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">nom</span>-see-<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">asp</span>=1<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">sg</span> bear-<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">erg</span>\n:\u2018the bear saw me\u2019\n\nThe direct-inverse contrast can be elicited with examples such as the following. In the inverse, the transitive direct object is coreferential with the subject in the preceding clause.\n\nDirect:\n\n;3) w\u00edn\u0161 i-q\u0313\u00ednu-\u0161ana wapaan\u0142\u00e1-an ku  i-\u0294\u00ed\u019b\u0313iyawi-ya paan\u00e1y \n:man 3<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">nom</span>-see-<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">asp</span> grizzly-<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">acc</span> and :3<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">nom</span>-kill-<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">pst</span> 3<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">acc.sg</span>\n:\u2018the man saw the grizzly and he killed it\u2019\n\nInverse:\n\n;4) w\u00edn\u0161 i-q\u0313\u00ednu-\u0161ana wapaan\u0142\u00e1-an ku  p\u00e1-\u0294i\u019b\u0313iyawi-ya\n:man  3<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">nom</span>-see-<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">asp</span> grizzly-<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">acc</span> and <span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">inv</span>-kill-<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">pst</span>\n:\u2018the man saw the grizzly and it killed him\u2019\n\nThe inverse (marked by the verbal prefix ''p\u00e1-'') retains its transitive status, and a patient nominal is case marked accusative.\n\n;5) ku  p\u00e1-\u0294i\u019b\u0313iyawi-ya w\u00edn\u0161-na\n:and <span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">inv</span>-kill-<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">pst</span>   man-<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">acc</span>\n:\u2018and it killed the man\u2019 (= \u2018and the man was killed by it\u2019)\n\nA semantic inverse is also marked by the same verbal prefix ''p\u00e1-''.\n\nDirect:\n\n;6) q\u0313\u00ednu-\u0161ana=ma\u0161\n:</span>see-<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">asp</span>=<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">1sg/2sg</span>\n:\u2018I saw you\u2019\n\nInverse:\n\n;7) p\u00e1-q\u0313inu-\u0161ana=nam\n:<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">inv</span>-see-<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">asp</span> =<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">2sg</span>\n:\u2018you saw me\u2019\n\nIn Speech Act Participant (SAP) and third-person transitive involvement, direction marking is as follows:\n\nDirect:\n\n;8) \u00e1-q\u0313inu-\u0161ana=a\u0161 paan\u00e1y\n:<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">obv</span>-see-<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">asp</span>=<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">1sg</span> 3<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">sg.acc</span>\n:\u2018I saw him/her/it\u2019\n\nInverse:\n\n;9) i-q\u0313\u00ednu-\u0161ana=a\u0161  p\u0268\u0301n\u0268m\n:3<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">nom</span>-see-<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">asp</span>=1<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">sg</span> 3<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">erg</span>\n:\u2018he/she/it saw me\u2019\n\n==Phonology==\nThe charts of consonants and vowels below are used in the Yakima Sahaptin (Ichishkiin) language:<ref>{{Cite book|title=A Grammar of Yakima Ichishk\u00edin Sahaptin|last=Jansen|first=Joana Worth|publisher=University of Oregon Graduate School|year=2010|isbn=|location=|pages=|quote=|via=}}</ref>\n\n===Consonants===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable IPA\" style=text-align:center\n|- \n! colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" | \n! rowspan=\"2\" | [[bilabial consonant|Bilabial]]\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[alveolar consonant|Alveolar]]\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Postalveolar consonant|Post-<br />alveolar]]\n! rowspan=\"2\" | [[Palatal consonant|Palatal]]\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[velar consonant|Velar]]\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[uvular consonant|Uvular]]\n! rowspan=\"2\" | [[glottal consonant|Glottal]]\n|-\n!<small>plain</small>\n! <small>[[lateral consonant|lateral]]</small>\n! <small>plain</small>\n! <small>[[Labialization|labialized]]</small>\n! <small>plain</small>\n! <small>[[Labialization|labialized]]</small>\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | [[Stop consonant|Plosive]]\n!<small>plain</small>\n| p\n| t\n| \n|\n| \n| k\n| k\u02b7\n| q\n| q\u02b7\n| \u0294\n|-\n! <small>[[ejective consonant|ejective]]</small>\n| p\u02bc\n| t\u02bc\n| \n|\n| \n| k\u02bc\n| k\u02b7\u02bc\n| q\u02bc\n| q\u02b7\u02bc\n| \n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[fricative consonant|Fricative]]\n| \n| s\n| \u026c\n|\u0283\n| \n| x\n| x\u02b7\n| \u03c7\n| \u03c7\u02b7\n| h\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Affricate consonant|Affricate]]\n!<small>plain</small>\n|\n|ts\n|t\u026c\n|t\u0283\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!<small>[[Ejective consonant|ejective]]</small>\n|\n|ts\u02bc\n|t\u026c\u02bc\n|t\u0283\u02bc\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |[[Nasal consonant|Nasal]]\n| m\n| n\n| \n|\n| \n|\n| \n| \n| \n| \n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |[[Approximant consonant|Approximant]]\n|\n|\n|l\n|\n|j\n|\n|w\n|\n|\n|\n|}\n\n=== Vowels ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!\n![[Front vowel|Front]]\n![[Central vowel|Central]]\n![[Back vowel|Back]]\n|-\n![[Close vowel|High]]\n|i i\u02d0\n|\u0268\n|u u\u02d0\n|-\n![[Open vowel|Low]]\n|\n|a a\u02d0\n|\n|}\nVowels can also be accented (e.g. /\u00e1/).\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Sahaptian languages]]\n* [[Sahaptin people]]\n* [[Cayuse people|Cayuse]]\n* [[Palus (tribe)]]\n* [[Umatilla (tribe)]]\n* [[Walla Walla (tribe)]]\n* [[Yakama]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n{{more footnotes|date=January 2010}}\n\n* <cite id=\"refBeavert and Hargus2010\">Beavert, Virginia, and Sharon Hargus (2010).  ''Ichishkiin S\u0268\u0301nwit Yakama/Yakima Sahaptin Dictionary''.  Toppenish and Seattle: Heritage University and University of Washington Press.</cite>\n* <cite id=\"refHargus and Beavert2002\">Hargus, Sharon, and Virginia Beavert. (2002). Yakima Sahaptin clusters and epenthetic [\u0268].  ''Anthropological Linguistics'', 44.1-47.</cite>\n* <cite id=\"refJacobs1929\">Jacobs, Melville (1929).  [http://content.lib.washington.edu/u?/lctext,7620 Northwest Sahaptin Texts, 1].  ''University of Washington Publications in Anthropology'' 2:6:175-244.  Seattle: University of Washington Press.</cite>\n* <cite id=\"refJacobs1931\">Jacobs, Melville (1931).  [http://content.lib.washington.edu/u?/lctext,7974 A Sketch of Northern Sahaptin Grammar].  ''University of Washington Publications in Anthropology'' 4:2:85-292.  Seattle: University of Washington Press.</cite>\n* <cite id=\"refJacobs1934\">Jacobs, Melville (1934).  ''Northwest Sahaptin Texts''.  English language only.  ''Columbia University Contributions to Anthropology'' 19, Part 1.  New York: Columbia University Press.</cite>\n* <cite id=\"refJacobs1937\">Jacobs, Melville (1937).  ''Northwest Sahaptin Texts''.  Sahaptin language only.  ''Columbia University Contributions to Anthropology'' 19, Part 2.  New York: Columbia University Press.</cite>\n* <cite id=\"refMithun1999\">Mithun, Marianne. (1999). ''The languages of Native North America''. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press. {{ISBN|0-521-23228-7}} (hbk); {{ISBN|0-521-29875-X}}.</cite>\n* <cite id=\"refRigsby and Rude1996\">Rigsby, Bruce, and Noel Rude. (1996).  Sketch of Sahaptin, a Sahaptian Language.  In ''Languages'', ed. by Ives Goddard, pp.&nbsp;666\u2013692. [[Handbook of North American Indians]], Volume 17. Washington, D.C.: Smithsonian Institution.</cite>\n* <cite id=\"refRude1988\">Rude, Noel. (1988). Pronominal prefixes in Klikitat Sahaptin. In ''Papers from the 1988 Hokan-Penutian Languages Workshop: Held at the University of Oregon, June 16\u201318, 1988'', compiled by Scott DeLancey, pp.&nbsp;181\u2013197.  Eugene, Oregon: University of Oregon Papers in Linguistics.</cite>\n* <cite id=\"refRude1994\">Rude, Noel. (1994). Direct, inverse and passive in Northwest Sahaptin.  In ''Voice and Inversion'', ed. by T. Giv\u00f3n.  Typological Studies in Language, Vol. 28:101-119.  Amsterdam: John Benjamins.</cite>\n* <cite id=\"refRude2009\">Rude, Noel. (2006).  [http://lingserver.arts.ubc.ca/linguistics/sites/default/files/Rude_2006.pdf Proto-Sahaptian vocalism.] ''University of British Columbia Working Papers in Linguistics'', Volume 18: 264-277.</cite>\n* <cite id=\"refRude2009\">Rude, Noel. (2009).  [https://www.sfu.ca/nwjl/Articles/V003_N03/RudeTransitivityInSahaptin.html Transitivity in Sahaptin.] ''Northwest Journal of Linguistics'', Vol. 3, Issue 3, pp.&nbsp;1\u201337.</cite>\n* <cite id=\"refRude2009\">Rude, Noel. (2011).  [http://lingserver.arts.ubc.ca/linguistics/sites/default/files/2011_Rude.pdf External possession, obviation, and kinship in Umatilla Sahaptin.] ''University of British Columbia Working Papers in Linguistics'', Volume 30: 351-365.</cite>\n* <cite id=\"refRude2009\">Rude, Noel. (2012).  [http://lingserver.arts.ubc.ca/linguistics/sites/default/files/2012_Rude.pdf Reconstructing Proto-Sahaptian Sounds.] ''University of British Columbia Working Papers in Linguistics'', Volume 32: 292-324.</cite>\n* <cite id=\"refRude2009\">Rude, Noel. (2014). ''Umatilla Dictionary''.  Seattle & London: University of Washington Press.</cite>\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Cite book\n| publisher = Heritage University, University of Washington Press\n| last = Beavert\n| first = Virginia\n|author2=Sharon Hargus\n | title = Ichishkiin sinwit Yakama/Yakima Sahaptin Dictionary\n| location = Toppenish, WA\n| accessdate = 2012-07-10\n| year = 2010\n| url = http://depts.washington.edu/sahaptin/\n}}\n*{{Cite web\n| title = Sahaptin Noun Dictionary (Yakama Dialect)\n| accessdate = 2012-07-10\n| url = http://www.native-languages.org/sahaptin.htm\n}}\n*{{Cite news\n| last = Muir\n| first = Pat\n| title = Virginia Beavert keeping Sahaptin language alive\n| work = Yakima Herald-Republic\n| accessdate = 2012-07-10\n| date = 2010-02-20\n| url = http://www.yakima-herald.com/stories/2010/02/20/virginia-beavert-keeping-sahaptin-language-alive\n}}\n*{{Cite web\n |last       = McDonald\n |first      = Rachael\n |title      = Yakama Elder Keeps Language Alive\n |work       = KLCC Eugene Oregon NPR\n |access-date = 2012-07-10\n |date       = 2009-05-25\n |url        = http://www.klcc.org/Feature.asp?FeatureID=1127\n|archive-url = https://archive.is/20130415113434/http://www.klcc.org/Feature.asp?FeatureID=1127\n|url-status   = dead\n|archive-date = 2013-04-15\n}}\n*{{Cite news\n| last = Martin\n| first = Shelby\n| title = Rare Yakama Sahaptin language taught at university\n| work = Spokesman.com, The Spokesman-Review\n| accessdate = 2012-07-10\n| date = 2009-02-14\n| url = http://www.spokesman.com/stories/2009/feb/14/rare-yakama-sahaptin-language-taught-at-university/\n}}\n*{{Cite web\n| last = Dadigan\n| first = Marc\n| title = Guardians of Language\n| work = CAScade, UO College of Arts and Sciences\n| accessdate = 2012-07-10\n| year = 2010\n| url = http://cascade.uoregon.edu/spring2010/features/feature1/feature-one/\n}}\n*ELAR archive of [http://elar.soas.ac.uk/deposit/0220 Yakima (Sahaptin) language documentation materials]\n*{{Cite web|url = https://scholarsbank.uoregon.edu/xmlui/bitstream/handle/1794/10901/Jansen_Joana_Worth_phd2010sp.pdf?sequence=1|title = Grammar Of Yakima Ichishk\u00edin /Sahaptin|last =Jansen|first =Joana Worth|date=2010|website=[PDF|publisher=|access-date=}}\n\n{{Penutian languages}}\n{{Languages of Oregon}}\n\n[[Category:Sahaptian languages]]\n[[Category:Indigenous languages of Washington (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox language\n|name=Sahaptin\n'''|states=[[United States]]'''\n|region=[[Washington (U.S. state)|Washington]], [[Oregon]], and [[Idaho]]\n|ethnicity={{sigfig|9,820|1}}<!--data supports 1 sig fig--> [[Sahaptin]]s (1977)<ref name=e18/>\n|speakers=100\u2013125\n|date=2007\n|ref=e18\n|familycolor=American\n|fam1=[[Plateau Penutian languages|Plateau Penutian]]\n|fam2=[[Sahaptian languages|Sahaptian]]\n|linglist=qot\n|lingname=Sahaptin\n|lc1=uma  |ld1=[[Umatilla language|Umatilla]] \n|lc2=waa  |ld2=[[Walla Walla tribe|Walla Walla]] \n|lc3=yak  |ld3=[[Yakama Nation|Yakama]] \n|lc4=tqn  |ld4=[[Warm Springs tribes|Tenino]] \n|glotto=saha1240\n|glottorefname=Sahaptin\n}}\n\n'''Sahaptin''' or '''Shahaptin''' is one of the two-language [[Sahaptian languages|Sahaptian]] branch of the [[Plateau Penutian languages|Plateau Penutian]] family spoken in a section of the northwestern plateau along the [[Columbia River]] and its tributaries in southern Washington, northern Oregon, and southwestern Idaho, in the [[United States]].;<ref>[[#refMithun1999|Mithun, 1999]]</ref> the other language is [[Nez Perce language|Nez Perce]] or ''Niimi'ipuut\u00edmt''. Many of the tribes that surrounded the land were skilled with horses and trading with one another; some tribes were known for their [[horse breeding]] which resulted in today's [[Appaloosa]] or [[Cayuse horse]].\n\nThe word ''Sahaptin/Shahaptin'' is not the one used by the tribes that speak it, but from the Columbia Salish name, '''S\u0127\u00e1pt\u0259n\u0259xw / S-h\u00e1ptinoxw''', which means \"stranger in the land\". This is the name [[Wenatchi]] (in Sahaptin: Win\u00e1tshapam) and Kawaxchinl\u00e1ma (who speak Columbia Salish), traditionally call the [[Nez Perce people]]. Early white explorers mistakenly applied the name to all the various Sahaptin speaking people, as well as to the Nez Perce. Sahaptin is spoken by various tribes of the Washington Reservations; Yakama, Warm Springs, Umatilla; and also spoken in many smaller communities, including one in Oregon, Celilo.\n\nThe [[Yakama]] tribal cultural resources program has been promoting the use of the traditional name of the language, ''Ichishk\u00edin S\u0268\u0301nwit'' (\u2033this language\u2033), instead of the Salish term ''Sahaptin''.<ref>Beavert, Virginia and Hargus, Sharon ''Ichishk\u00edin s\u0268\u0301nwit yakama = Yakima Sahaptin dictionary''. Toppenish, Wash.: Heritage University, Seattle: in association with the University of Washington Press, 2009; 492 pp. OCLC 268797329.</ref>\n\n==Dialects==\nSahaptin has three mutually intelligible dialects in a [[dialect cluster]] :<ref>Sharon Hargus 2012, [http://faculty.washington.edu/sharon/1P_Clitics_NW_Sahaptin.pdf First position clitics in Northwest Sahaptin]</ref>\n*Northern Sahaptin group\n**Northwest Sahaptin dialect cluster: '''[[Klickitat people|Klickitat (Klikitat)]]''' (Yakama name: Xw\u00e1lxwaypam or L'ataxat), '''[[Cowlitz people|Tainapam]]''' (Taidnapam / T\u00e1ytnapam or Upper Cowlitz), Upper Nisqually (Meshal / Mashel or Mica'l, also known as Mishalpam), '''[[Yakama|Yakama (Yakima)]]''' (Lower or Yakama proper, autonym: M\u00e1machatpam), '''[[Kittitas people|Kittitas]]''' (Upper Yakama, autonym: Pshw\u00e1napam or Pshwanpawam)\n**Northeast Sahaptin dialect cluster: '''[[Wanapum|Wanapum (Wanapam)]]''' (W\u00e1napam), '''[[Palus people|Palouse (Palus)]]''' (Yakama name: Pel\u00fauspem), Lower Snake (Chamnapam, Wauyukma, and Naxiyampam), '''[[Walla Walla tribe|Walla Walla]]''' (Waluulapan)\n*Southern Sahaptin group (Columbia River cluster): '''[[Umatilla language|Umatilla]]''' (Rock Creek Indians, Yakama name: Amatalamlama; Imatalamlama), Skin-pah (Sk'in tribe or Sawpaw, also known as Fall Bridge and Rock Creek people or K'mill\u00e1ma, a Tenino subtribe; perhaps another Yakama name for the Umatilla, who were known as Rock Creek Indians), '''[[Tenino people|Tenino]]''' (Tygh Valley dialect of the [[Tygh people|Tygh]] (Taih, Tyigh or Tayx\u026b\u00e1ma) or \"Upper Deschutes\", Celilo dialect of the [[Wyam people|Wyam (Way\u00e1m\u026b\u00e1ma)]] (Yakama name: Way\u00e1mpam) or \"Lower Deschutes\", also known as \"Celilo Indians\", Tenino dialect of the [[Dalles Tenino people|Dalles Tenino]] or \"Tinainu (Tinaynu\u026b\u00e1ma)\"; John Day dialect oft the [[Dock-Spus people|Dock-Spus (Tukspush or Takspas\u026b\u00e1ma)]] or \"John Day.\")\n\n==Grammar==\nThere are published grammars,<ref>[[#refJacobs1931|Jacobs, 1931]].</ref><ref>[[#refRigsby and Rude1996|Rigsby and Rude, 1996]].</ref> a recent dictionary,<ref>[[#refBeavert & Hargus2009|Beavert & Hargus, 2009]].</ref> and a corpus of published texts.<ref>[[#refJacobs1929|Jacobs, 1929]].</ref><ref>[[#refJacobs1937|Jacobs, 1937]].</ref>  Sahaptin has a [[split ergativity|split ergative]] syntax, with direct-inverse voicing and several applicative constructions.<ref>[[#refRude2009|Rude, 2009]].</ref>\n\nThe [[ergative case]] inflects third-person nominals only when the direct object is first- or second-person (the examples below are from the Umatilla dialect):\n\n;1) i-q\u0313\u00ednu-\u0161ana y\u00e1ka  paan\u00e1y\n:3<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">nom</span>-see-<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">asp</span> bear 3<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">acc.sg</span>\n:\u2018the bear saw him\u2019\n\n;2) i-q\u0313\u00ednu-\u0161ana=a\u0161  y\u00e1ka-n\u0268m\n:3<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">nom</span>-see-<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">asp</span>=1<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">sg</span> bear-<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">erg</span>\n:\u2018the bear saw me\u2019\n\nThe direct-inverse contrast can be elicited with examples such as the following. In the inverse, the transitive direct object is coreferential with the subject in the preceding clause.\n\nDirect:\n\n;3) w\u00edn\u0161 i-q\u0313\u00ednu-\u0161ana wapaan\u0142\u00e1-an ku  i-\u0294\u00ed\u019b\u0313iyawi-ya paan\u00e1y \n:man 3<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">nom</span>-see-<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">asp</span> grizzly-<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">acc</span> and :3<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">nom</span>-kill-<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">pst</span> 3<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">acc.sg</span>\n:\u2018the man saw the grizzly and he killed it\u2019\n\nInverse:\n\n;4) w\u00edn\u0161 i-q\u0313\u00ednu-\u0161ana wapaan\u0142\u00e1-an ku  p\u00e1-\u0294i\u019b\u0313iyawi-ya\n:man  3<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">nom</span>-see-<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">asp</span> grizzly-<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">acc</span> and <span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">inv</span>-kill-<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">pst</span>\n:\u2018the man saw the grizzly and it killed him\u2019\n\nThe inverse (marked by the verbal prefix ''p\u00e1-'') retains its transitive status, and a patient nominal is case marked accusative.\n\n;5) ku  p\u00e1-\u0294i\u019b\u0313iyawi-ya w\u00edn\u0161-na\n:and <span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">inv</span>-kill-<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">pst</span>   man-<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">acc</span>\n:\u2018and it killed the man\u2019 (= \u2018and the man was killed by it\u2019)\n\nA semantic inverse is also marked by the same verbal prefix ''p\u00e1-''.\n\nDirect:\n\n;6) q\u0313\u00ednu-\u0161ana=ma\u0161\n:</span>see-<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">asp</span>=<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">1sg/2sg</span>\n:\u2018I saw you\u2019\n\nInverse:\n\n;7) p\u00e1-q\u0313inu-\u0161ana=nam\n:<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">inv</span>-see-<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">asp</span> =<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">2sg</span>\n:\u2018you saw me\u2019\n\nIn Speech Act Participant (SAP) and third-person transitive involvement, direction marking is as follows:\n\nDirect:\n\n;8) \u00e1-q\u0313inu-\u0161ana=a\u0161 paan\u00e1y\n:<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">obv</span>-see-<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">asp</span>=<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">1sg</span> 3<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">sg.acc</span>\n:\u2018I saw him/her/it\u2019\n\nInverse:\n\n;9) i-q\u0313\u00ednu-\u0161ana=a\u0161  p\u0268\u0301n\u0268m\n:3<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">nom</span>-see-<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">asp</span>=1<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">sg</span> 3<span class=\"smallcaps\" style=\"font-variant:small-caps;\">erg</span>\n:\u2018he/she/it saw me\u2019\n\n==Phonology==\nThe charts of consonants and vowels below are used in the Yakima Sahaptin (Ichishkiin) language:<ref>{{Cite book|title=A Grammar of Yakima Ichishk\u00edin Sahaptin|last=Jansen|first=Joana Worth|publisher=University of Oregon Graduate School|year=2010|isbn=|location=|pages=|quote=|via=}}</ref>\n\n===Consonants===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable IPA\" style=text-align:center\n|- \n! colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" | \n! rowspan=\"2\" | [[bilabial consonant|Bilabial]]\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[alveolar consonant|Alveolar]]\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Postalveolar consonant|Post-<br />alveolar]]\n! rowspan=\"2\" | [[Palatal consonant|Palatal]]\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[velar consonant|Velar]]\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[uvular consonant|Uvular]]\n! rowspan=\"2\" | [[glottal consonant|Glottal]]\n|-\n!<small>plain</small>\n! <small>[[lateral consonant|lateral]]</small>\n! <small>plain</small>\n! <small>[[Labialization|labialized]]</small>\n! <small>plain</small>\n! <small>[[Labialization|labialized]]</small>\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | [[Stop consonant|Plosive]]\n!<small>plain</small>\n| p\n| t\n| \n|\n| \n| k\n| k\u02b7\n| q\n| q\u02b7\n| \u0294\n|-\n! <small>[[ejective consonant|ejective]]</small>\n| p\u02bc\n| t\u02bc\n| \n|\n| \n| k\u02bc\n| k\u02b7\u02bc\n| q\u02bc\n| q\u02b7\u02bc\n| \n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[fricative consonant|Fricative]]\n| \n| s\n| \u026c\n|\u0283\n| \n| x\n| x\u02b7\n| \u03c7\n| \u03c7\u02b7\n| h\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Affricate consonant|Affricate]]\n!<small>plain</small>\n|\n|ts\n|t\u026c\n|t\u0283\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!<small>[[Ejective consonant|ejective]]</small>\n|\n|ts\u02bc\n|t\u026c\u02bc\n|t\u0283\u02bc\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |[[Nasal consonant|Nasal]]\n| m\n| n\n| \n|\n| \n|\n| \n| \n| \n| \n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |[[Approximant consonant|Approximant]]\n|\n|\n|l\n|\n|j\n|\n|w\n|\n|\n|\n|}\n\n=== Vowels ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!\n![[Front vowel|Front]]\n![[Central vowel|Central]]\n![[Back vowel|Back]]\n|-\n![[Close vowel|High]]\n|i i\u02d0\n|\u0268\n|u u\u02d0\n|-\n![[Open vowel|Low]]\n|\n|a a\u02d0\n|\n|}\nVowels can also be accented (e.g. /\u00e1/).\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Sahaptian languages]]\n* [[Sahaptin people]]\n* [[Cayuse people|Cayuse]]\n* [[Palus (tribe)]]\n* [[Umatilla (tribe)]]\n* [[Walla Walla (tribe)]]\n* [[Yakama]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n{{more footnotes|date=January 2010}}\n\n* <cite id=\"refBeavert and Hargus2010\">Beavert, Virginia, and Sharon Hargus (2010).  ''Ichishkiin S\u0268\u0301nwit Yakama/Yakima Sahaptin Dictionary''.  Toppenish and Seattle: Heritage University and University of Washington Press.</cite>\n* <cite id=\"refHargus and Beavert2002\">Hargus, Sharon, and Virginia Beavert. (2002). Yakima Sahaptin clusters and epenthetic [\u0268].  ''Anthropological Linguistics'', 44.1-47.</cite>\n* <cite id=\"refJacobs1929\">Jacobs, Melville (1929).  [http://content.lib.washington.edu/u?/lctext,7620 Northwest Sahaptin Texts, 1].  ''University of Washington Publications in Anthropology'' 2:6:175-244.  Seattle: University of Washington Press.</cite>\n* <cite id=\"refJacobs1931\">Jacobs, Melville (1931).  [http://content.lib.washington.edu/u?/lctext,7974 A Sketch 