{"title_page": "List of presidents of the United States by home state", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\nThese lists give the [[U.S. state|state]]s of primary affiliation and of birth for each [[President of the United States|president]] of the [[United States]].\n\n==Birth places==\nTwenty-one states have claimed the distinction of being the birthplace of a president. One president's ''birth state'' is in dispute; North and South Carolina (British colonies at the time) both lay claim to [[Andrew Jackson]], who was born in 1777, in the [[Waxhaws|Waxhaw region]] along their common border. Jackson himself considered South Carolina as his birth state.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2011/03/06/AR2011030603406.html?wprss=rss_print/asection|title=Old fight lingers over Old Hickory's roots|last=Collings|first=Jeffrey|date=March 7, 2011|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|publisher=The Washington Post Company|location=Washington, D.C.}}</ref> Born on December 5, 1782, [[Martin Van Buren]] was the first president born an [[American citizen]] (and not a [[British subject]]).<ref>{{cite web| last=Glass| first=Andrew| date=July 21, 2014| title=Van Buren slips into coma, July 21, 1862| publisher=Politico| location=Arlington County, Virginia| url=https://www.politico.com/story/2014/07/this-day-in-politics-martin-van-buren-coma-109149| accessdate=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe term [[Virginia dynasty]] is sometimes used to describe the fact that four of the first five U.S. presidents were from Virginia. The number of presidents born per state, counting Jackson as being from South Carolina, are:\n* One: [[Arkansas]], [[California]], [[Connecticut]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], [[Hawaii]], [[Illinois]], [[Iowa]], [[Kentucky]], [[Missouri]], [[Nebraska]], [[New Hampshire]], [[New Jersey]], [[Pennsylvania]], and [[South Carolina]]\n* Two: [[North Carolina]], [[Texas]], and [[Vermont]]\n* Four: [[Massachusetts]]\n* Five: [[New York (state)|New York city]]\n* Seven: [[Ohio]]\n* Eight: [[Virginia]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Date of birth !! President !! Birthplace !! State{{ref|state_colony|\u2020}} of birth !! In office\n|-\n| {{dts|February 22, 1732}}  || {{sortname|George|Washington}} ||  [[Westmoreland County, Virginia|Westmoreland County]] || {{sort|virga|[[Colony of Virginia|Virginia]]}}{{ref|state_colony|\u2020}} || {{sort|01|(1st) April 30, 1789 \u2013 March 4, 1797}}\n|-\n| {{dts|October 30, 1735}}  || {{sortname|John|Adams}} || [[Braintree, Massachusetts|Braintree]]|| {{sort|Massaa|[[Province of Massachusetts Bay|Massachusetts]]}}{{ref|state_colony|\u2020}} || {{sort|02|(2nd) March 4, 1797 \u2013 March 4, 1801}}\n|-\n| {{dts|April 13, 1743}}* || {{sortname|Thomas|Jefferson}}  || [[Shadwell, Virginia|Shadwell]] || {{sort|virgb|Virginia}}{{ref|state_colony|\u2020}} || {{sort|03|(3rd) March 4, 1801 \u2013 March 4, 1809}}\n|-\n| {{dts|March 16, 1751}} || {{sortname|James|Madison}} || [[Port Conway, Virginia|Port Conway]] || {{sort|virgc|Virginia}}{{ref|state_colony|\u2020}} || {{sort|04|(4th) March 4, 1809 \u2013 March 4, 1817}}\n|-\n| {{dts|April 28, 1758}} || {{sortname|James|Monroe}} || [[Monroe Hall, Virginia|Monroe Hall]] || {{sort|virgd|Virginia}}{{ref|state_colony|\u2020}} || {{sort|05|(5th) March 4, 1817 \u2013 March 4, 1825}}\n|-\n| {{dts|March 15, 1767}} || {{sortname|Andrew|Jackson}} || [[Waxhaws|Waxhaws Region]] || {{sort|Sou|[[Province of South Carolina|South Carolina]]}}{{ref|state_colony|\u2020}} || {{sort|07|(7th) March 4, 1829 \u2013 March 4, 1837}}\n|-\n| {{dts|July 11, 1767}} ||  {{sortname|John Quincy|Adams|John Quincy Adams}} || Braintree || {{sort|Massab|Massachusetts}}{{ref|state_colony|\u2020}} || {{sort|06|(6th) March 4, 1825 \u2013 March 4, 1829}}\n|-\n| {{dts|February 9, 1773}} || {{sortname|William Henry|Harrison|William Henry Harrison}} || [[North Bend, Ohio|Charles City County]] || {{sort|virge|Virginia}}{{ref|state_colony|\u