333|label='''[[Jimmy Carter|Carter]]'''|marksize=6}}\n{{Location map~|USA|position=right|lat=41.31|long=-72.923611|label='''[[George W. Bush|G.W. Bush]]'''|marksize=6}}\n{{Location map~|USA|position=right|lat=33.667172|long=-93.596489|label='''[[Bill Clinton|Clinton]]'''|marksize=6}}\n{{Location map~|USA|position=right|lat=27.95|long=-105.55|outside=1<!-- Latitude is at 27.95 and longitude is at -105.55 to allow for the name and place to appear on display; actual latitude is 21.2998, and actual longitude is -157.8335 -->|label='''[[Barack Obama|Obama]]'''|marksize=6}}\n{{Location map~|USA|position=right|lat=40.703611|long=-73.798889|label='''[[Donald Trump|Trump]]'''|marksize=6}}\n}}\n\n== States of primary affiliation ==\n{{See also|List of residences of Presidents of the United States}}\nA list of U.S. presidents including the state with which each was primarily affiliated, due to residence, professional career, and electoral history. This is  not necessarily the state in which the president was born. Eighteen presidents (denoted with an asterisk) primarily resided in states other than their respective birth states, which are listed above.\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"text-align: left;\"\n! State !! <abbr title=\"Number of presidents\">#</abbr> !! class=\"unsortable\"|Presidents (''in order of presidency'')\n|-\n| {{flag|New York}}\n| 7\n| [[Martin Van Buren]] (8), [[Millard Fillmore]] (13), [[Chester A. Arthur]]* (21), [[Grover Cleveland]]* (22, 24), [[Theodore Roosevelt]] (26), [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] (32), [[Donald Trump]] (45)<!-- TRUMP MAY CLAIM TO BE A RESIDENT OF FLORIDA NOW, BUT THAT DOES NOT MAKE IT HIS STATE OF PRIMARY AFFILIATION. DO NOT CHANGE.-->\n|-\n| {{flag|Ohio}}\n| 7\n| [[William Henry Harrison]]* (9), [[Ulysses S. Grant]] (18),<!-- THOUGH GRANT WAS A CITIZEN OF ILLINOIS DURING HIS PRESIDENCY, HE ONLY RESIDED THERE FOR A SHORT PERIOD OF TIME, AND SPENT MOST OF PRE-PRESIDENCY YEARS IN OHIO. DO NOT CHANGE.--> [[Rutherford B. Hayes]] (19), [[James A. Garfield]] (20), [[William McKinley]] (25), [[William Howard Taft]] (27), [[Warren G. Harding]] (29)\n|-\n| {{flag|Virginia}}\n| 5\n| [[George Washington]] (1), [[Thomas Jefferson]] (3), [[James Madison]] (4), [[James Monroe]] (5), [[John Tyler]] (10)\n|-\n| {{flag|Massachusetts}}\n| 4\n| [[John Adams]] (2), [[John Quincy Adams]] (6), [[Calvin Coolidge]]* (30), [[John F. Kennedy]] (35)\n|-\n| {{flag|Tennessee}}\n| 3\n| [[Andrew Jackson]]* (7), [[James K. Polk]]* (11), [[Andrew Johnson]]* (17)\n|-\n| {{flag|Texas}}\n| 3\n| [[Lyndon B. Johnson]] (36), [[George H. W. Bush]]* (41), [[George W. Bush]]* (43)\n|-\n| {{flag|California}}\n| 2\n| [[Richard Nixon]] (37), [[Ronald Reagan]]* (40)\n|-\n| {{flag|Illinois}}\n| 2\n| [[Abraham Lincoln]]* (16), [[Barack Obama]]* (44)\n|-\n| {{flag|Arkansas}}\n| 1\n| [[Bill Clinton]] (42)\n|-\n| {{flag|Georgia (U.S. state)|name=Georgia}}\n| 1\n| [[Jimmy Carter]] (39)\n|-\n| {{flag|Indiana}}\n| 1\n| [[Benjamin Harrison]]* (23)\n|-\n| {{flag|Iowa}}\n| 1\n| [[Herbert Hoover]]* (31)<!--DO NOT CHANGE. HOOVER ACQUIRED HIS PALO ALTO HOME IN 1920, BUT HIS TRUE HOME WAS IN D.C. AS SECRETARY OF COMMERCE. GIVEN HIS TRAVELS AROUND EARTH, HE SPENT MORE TIME IN IOWA THAN ANY OTHER PLACE--> \n|-\n| {{flag|Kansas}}\n| 1\n| [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]]* (34)\n|-\n| {{flag|Kentucky}}\n| 1\n| [[Zachary Taylor]]* (12)\n|-\n| {{flag|Michigan}}\n| 1\n| [[Gerald Ford]]* (38)\n|-\n| {{flag|Missouri}}\n| 1\n| [[Harry S. Truman]] (33)\n|-\n| nowrap|{{flag|New Hampshire}}\n| 1\n| [[Franklin Pierce]] (14)\n|-\n| {{flag|New Jersey}}\n| 1\n| [[Woodrow Wilson]]* (28)\n|-\n| {{flag|Pennsylvania}}\n|1\n| [[James Buchanan]] (15)\n|-\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.nps.gov/nr/travel/presidents/list_of_sites.html American Presidents Sites - Discover Our Shared Heritage Travel Itinerary] from the National Park Service\n{{Lists of US Presidents and Vice Presidents}}\n\n[[Category:Lists relating to the United States presidency|Presidents, home state]]\n[[Category:Birthplaces|Presidents of the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\nThese lists give the [[U.S. state|state]]s of primary affiliation and of birth for each [[President of the United States|president]] of the [[United States]].\n\n==Birth places==\nTwenty-one states have claimed the distinction of being the birthplace of a president. One president's ''birth state'' is in dispute; North and South Carolina (British colonies at the time) both lay claim to [[Andrew Jackson]], who was born in 1777, in the [[Waxhaws|Waxhaw region]] along their common border. Jackson himself considered South Carolina as his birth state.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2011/03/06/AR2011030603406.html?wprss=rss_print/asection|title=Old fight lingers over Old Hickory's roots|last=Collings|first=Jeffrey|date=March 7, 2011|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|publisher=The Washington Post Company|location=Washington, D.C.}}</ref> Born on December 5, 1782, [[Martin Van Buren]] was the first president born an [[American citizen]] (and not a [[British subject]]).<ref>{{cite web| last=Glass| first=Andrew| date=July 21, 2014| title=Van Buren slips into coma, July 21, 1862| publisher=Politico| location=Arlington County, Virginia| url=https://www.politico.com/story/2014/07/this-day-in-politics-martin-van-buren-coma-109149| accessdate=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe term [[Virginia dynasty]] is sometimes used to describe the fact that four of the first five U.S. presidents were from Virginia. The number of presidents born per state, counting Jackson as being from South Carolina, are:\n* One: [[Arkansas]], [[California]], [[Connecticut]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], [[Hawaii]], [[Illinois]], [[Iowa]], [[Kentucky]], [[Missouri]], [[Nebraska]], [[New Hampshire]], [[New Jersey]], [[Pennsylvania]], and [[South Carolina]]\n* Two: [[North Carolina]], [[Texas]], and [[Vermont]]\n* Four: [[Massachusetts]]\n* Five: [[New York (state)|New York]]\n* Seven: [[Ohio]]\n* Eight: [[Virginia]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Date of birth !! President !! Birthplace !! State{{ref|state_colony|\u2020}} of birth !! In office\n|-\n| {{dts|February 22, 1732}}  || {{sortname|George|Washington}} ||  [[Westmoreland County, Virginia|Westmoreland County]] || {{sort|virga|[[Colony of Virginia|Virginia]]}}{{ref|state_colony|\u2020}} || {{sort|01|(1st) April 30, 1789 \u2013 March 4, 1797}}\n|-\n| {{dts|October 30, 1735}}  || {{sortname|John|Adams}} || [[Braintree, Massachusetts|Braintree]]|| {{sort|Massaa|[[Province of Massachusetts Bay|Massachusetts]]}}{{ref|state_colony|\u2020}} || {{sort|02|(2nd) March 4, 1797 \u2013 March 4, 1801}}\n|-\n| {{dts|April 13, 1743}}* || {{sortname|Thomas|Jefferson}}  || [[Shadwell, Virginia|Shadwell]] || {{sort|virgb|Virginia}}{{ref|state_colony|\u2020}} || {{sort|03|(3rd) March 4, 1801 \u2013 March 4, 1809}}\n|-\n| {{dts|March 16, 1751}} || {{sortname|James|Madison}} || [[Port Conway, Virginia|Port Conway]] || {{sort|virgc|Virginia}}{{ref|state_colony|\u2020}} || {{sort|04|(4th) March 4, 1809 \u2013 March 4, 1817}}\n|-\n| {{dts|April 28, 1758}} || {{sortname|James|Monroe}} || [[Monroe Hall, Virginia|Monroe Hall]] || {{sort|virgd|Virginia}}{{ref|state_colony|\u2020}} || {{sort|05|(5th) March 4, 1817 \u2013 March 4, 1825}}\n|-\n| {{dts|March 15, 1767}} || {{sortname|Andrew|Jackson}} || [[Waxhaws|Waxhaws Region]] || {{sort|Sou|[[Province of South Carolina|South Carolina]]}}{{ref|state_colony|\u2020}} || {{sort|07|(7th) March 4, 1829 \u2013 March 4, 1837}}\n|-\n| {{dts|July 11, 1767}} ||  {{sortname|John Quincy|Adams|John Quincy Adams}} || Braintree || {{sort|Massab|Massachusetts}}{{ref|state_colony|\u2020}} || {{sort|06|(6th) March 4, 1825 \u2013 March 4, 1829}}\n|-\n| {{dts|February 9, 1773}} || {{sortname|William Henry|Harrison|William Henry Harrison}} || [[North Bend, Ohio|Charles City County]] || {{sort|virge|Virginia}